# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: arm-riscv
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] In ARMv8-A, ARMv8-R, and ARMv9-A, an "Execution state" defines key characteristics of the processor’s environment.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] This includes the number of bits used in the primary processor registers, the supported instruction sets, and other aspects of the processor's execution environment.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] These versions of the ARM architecture support two Execution states: the 64-bit AArch64 state and the 32-bit AArch32 state.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] Extension: Data gathering hint (ARMv8.0-DGH).
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] AArch64 was introduced in ARMv8-A and is included in subsequent versions of ARMv8-A, and in all versions of ARMv9-A.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] It was also introduced in ARMv8-R as an option, after its introduction in ARMv8-A; it is not included in ARMv8-M.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] The main opcode for selecting which group an A64 instruction belongs to is at bits 25–28.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] Announced in October 2011, **ARMv8-A** represents a fundamental change to the ARM architecture.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] It adds an optional 64-bit Execution state, named "AArch64", and the associated new "A64" instruction set, in addition to a 32-bit Execution state, "AArch32", supporting the 32-bit "A32" (original 32-bit ARM) and "T32" (Thumb/Thumb-2) instruction sets.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] The latter instruction sets provide user-space compatibility with the existing 32-bit ARMv7-A architecture.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] ARMv8-A allows 32-bit applications to be executed in a 64-bit OS, and a 32-bit OS to be under the control of a 64-bit hypervisor.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] ARM announced their Cortex-A53 and Cortex-A57 cores on 30 October 2012.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] Apple was the first to release an ARMv8-A compatible core (Cyclone) in a consumer product (iPhone 5S).
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] AppliedMicro, using an FPGA, was the first to demo ARMv8-A.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] The first ARMv8-A SoC from Samsung is the Exynos 5433 used in the Galaxy Note 4, which features two clusters of four Cortex-A57 and Cortex-A53 cores in a big.LITTLE configuration; but it only runs in AArch32 mode.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] ARMv8-A includes VFPv3/v4 and advanced SIMD (Neon) as standard features in both AArch32 and AArch64.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] It also adds cryptography instructions supporting AES, SHA-1/SHA-256 and finite field arithmetic.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] An ARMv8-A processor can support one or both of AArch32 and AArch64; it may support AArch32 and AArch64 at lower Exception levels and only AArch64 at higher Exception levels.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] For example, the ARM Cortex-A32 supports only AArch32, the ARM Cortex-A34 supports only AArch64, and the ARM Cortex-A72 supports both AArch64 and AArch32.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] An ARMv9-A processor must support AArch64 at all Exception levels, and may support AArch32 at EL0.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] In December 2014, ARMv8.1-A, an update with "incremental benefits over v8.0", was announced.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] The enhancements fell into two categories: changes to the instruction set, and changes to the exception model and memory translation.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] ARMv8.2-A was announced in January 2016.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] The Scalable Vector Extension (SVE) is licensed as "an optional extension to the ARMv8.2-A architecture and newer" developed specifically for vectorization of high-performance computing scientific workloads.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] The specification allows for ARM licensees to choose a hard-coded architectural register width between 128 and 2048 bits in multiples of 128.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] The extension is complementary to and does not replace the NEON extensions.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] A 512-bit SVE variant has already been implemented on the Fugaku supercomputer using the Fujitsu A64FX ARM processor; this computer was the fastest supercomputer in the world for two years, from June 2020 to May 2022.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] A more flexible version, 2x256 SVE, was implemented by the AWS Graviton3 ARM processor.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] SVE is supported by GCC, with GCC 8 supporting automatic vectorization and GCC 10 supporting C intrinsics.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] As of July 2020, LLVM and clang support C and IR intrinsics.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] ARM's own fork of LLVM supports auto-vectorization.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] In October 2016, ARMv8.3-A was announced.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] ARMv8.3-A architecture is now supported by (at least) GCC 7.0.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] In November 2017, ARMv8.4-A was announced.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] In September 2018, ARMv8.5-A was announced.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] On 2 August 2019, Google announced Android will adopt Memory Tagging Extension (MTE).
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] ARMv9-A's baseline is all features from ARMv8.5.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] In September 2019, ARMv8.6-A was announced.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] For example, fine-grained traps, Wait-for-Event (WFE) instructions, EnhancedPAC2 and FPAC.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] The bfloat16 extensions for SVE and Neon are mainly for deep learning use.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] In September 2020, ARMv8.7-A was announced.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] In September 2021, ARMv8.8-A and ARMv9.3-A were announced.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] LLVM 15 supports ARMv8.8-A and ARMv9.3-A.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] Optional AArch64 support was added to the Armv8-R profile, with the first Arm core implementing it being the Cortex-R82.
[src:arm-riscv/aarch64] It adds the A64 instruction set, with some changes to the memory barrier instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Due to their low costs, low power consumption, and low heat generation, ARM processors are useful for light, portable, battery-powered devices, including smartphones, laptops, and tablet computers, as well as embedded systems.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] However, ARM processors are also used for desktops and servers, including Fugaku, the world's fastest supercomputer from 2020 to 2022.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] With over 230 billion ARM chips produced, since at least 2003, and with its dominance increasing every year, ARM is the most widely used family of instruction set architectures.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] There have been several generations of the ARM design.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] The original ARM1 used a 32-bit internal structure but had a 26-bit address space that limited it to 64 MB of main memory.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] This limitation was removed in the ARMv3 series, which has a 32-bit address space, and several additional generations up to ARMv7 remained 32-bit.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Released in 2011, the ARMv8-A architecture added support for a 64-bit address space and 64-bit arithmetic with its new 32-bit fixed-length instruction set.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm Holdings has also released a series of additional instruction sets for different roles: the "Thumb" extensions add both 32- and 16-bit instructions for improved code density, while Jazelle added instructions for directly handling Java bytecode.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] More recent changes include the addition of simultaneous multithreading (SMT) for improved performance or fault tolerance.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Acorn Computers' first widely successful design was the BBC Micro, introduced in December 1981.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] This was a relatively conventional machine based on the MOS Technology 6502 CPU but ran at roughly double the performance of competing designs like the Apple II due to its use of faster dynamic random-access memory (DRAM).
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Typical DRAM of the era ran at about 2 MHz; Acorn arranged a deal with Hitachi for a supply of faster 4 MHz parts.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Machines of the era generally shared memory between the processor and the framebuffer, which allowed the processor to quickly update the contents of the screen without having to perform separate input/output (I/O).
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] As the timing of the video display is exacting, the video hardware had to have priority access to that memory.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Due to a quirk of the 6502's design, the CPU left the memory untouched for half of the time.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Thus by running the CPU at 1 MHz, the video system could read data during those down times, taking up the total 2 MHz bandwidth of the RAM.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] In the BBC Micro, the use of 4 MHz RAM allowed the same technique to be used, but running at twice the speed.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] This allowed it to outperform any similar machine on the market.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] 1981 was also the year that the IBM Personal Computer was introduced.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Using the recently introduced Intel 8088, a 16-bit CPU compared to the 6502's 8-bit design, it offered higher overall performance.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Its introduction changed the desktop computer market radically: what had been largely a hobby and gaming market emerging over the prior five years began to change to a must-have business tool where the earlier 8-bit designs simply could not compete.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Even newer 32-bit designs were also coming to market, such as the Motorola 68000 and National Semiconductor NS32016.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Acorn began considering how to compete in this market and produced a new paper design named the Acorn Business Computer.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] They set themselves the goal of producing a machine with ten times the performance of the BBC Micro, but at the same price.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] This would outperform and underprice the PC.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] At the same time, the recent introduction of the Apple Lisa brought the graphical user interface (GUI) concept to a wider audience and suggested the future belonged to machines with a GUI.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] The Lisa, however, cost $9,995, as it was packed with support chips, large amounts of memory, and a hard disk drive, all very expensive then.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] The engineers then began studying all of the CPU designs available.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Their conclusion about the existing 16-bit designs was that they were a lot more expensive and were still "a bit crap", offering only slightly higher performance than their BBC Micro design.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] They also almost always demanded a large number of support chips to operate even at that level, which drove up the cost of the computer as a whole.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] These systems would simply not hit the design goal.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] They also considered the new 32-bit designs, but these cost even more and had the same issues with support chips.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] According to Sophie Wilson, all the processors tested at that time performed about the same, with about a 4 Mbit/s bandwidth.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Two key events led Acorn down the path to ARM.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] One was the publication of a series of reports from the University of California, Berkeley, which suggested that a simple chip design could nevertheless have extremely high performance, much higher than the latest 32-bit designs on the market.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] The second was a visit by Steve Furber and Sophie Wilson to the Western Design Center, a company run by Bill Mensch and his sister Kathryn, which had become the logical successor to the MOS team and was offering new versions like the WDC 65C02.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] The Acorn team saw high school students producing chip layouts on Apple II machines, which suggested that anyone could do it.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] In contrast, a visit to another design firm working on modern 32-bit CPU revealed a team with over a dozen members who were already on revision H of their design and yet it still contained bugs.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] This cemented their late 1983 decision to begin their own CPU design, the Acorn RISC Machine.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] The original Berkeley RISC designs were in some sense teaching systems, not designed specifically for outright performance.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] To the RISC's basic register-heavy and load/store concepts, ARM added a number of the well-received design notes of the 6502.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Primary among them was the ability to quickly service interrupts, which allowed the machines to offer reasonable input/output performance with no added external hardware.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] To offer interrupts with similar performance as the 6502, the ARM design limited its physical address space to 64 MB of total addressable space, requiring 26 bits of address.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] As instructions were 4 bytes (32 bits) long, and required to be aligned on 4-byte boundaries, the lower 2 bits of an instruction address were always zero.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] This meant the program counter (PC) only needed to be 24 bits, allowing it to be stored along with the eight bit processor flags in a single 32-bit register.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] That meant that upon receiving an interrupt, the entire machine state could be saved in a single operation, whereas had the PC been a full 32-bit value, it would require separate operations to store the PC and the status flags.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] This decision halved the interrupt overhead.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Another change, and among the most important in terms of practical real-world performance, was the modification of the instruction set to take advantage of page mode DRAM.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Recently introduced, page mode allowed subsequent accesses of memory to run twice as fast if they were roughly in the same location, or "page", in the DRAM chip.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Berkeley's design did not consider page mode and treated all memory equally.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] The ARM design added special vector-like memory access instructions, the "S-cycles", that could be used to fill or save multiple registers in a single page using page mode.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] This doubled memory performance when they could be used, and was especially important for graphics performance.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] The Berkeley RISC designs used register windows to reduce the number of register saves and restores performed in procedure calls; the ARM design did not adopt this.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Wilson developed the instruction set, writing a simulation of the processor in BBC BASIC that ran on a BBC Micro with a second 6502 processor.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] This convinced Acorn engineers they were on the right track.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Wilson approached Acorn's CEO, Hermann Hauser, and requested more resources.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Hauser gave his approval and assembled a small team to design the actual processor based on Wilson's instruction set architecture.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] The official Acorn RISC Machine project started in October 1983.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Acorn chose VLSI Technology as the "silicon partner", as they were a source of ROMs and custom chips for Acorn.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Acorn provided the design and VLSI provided the layout and production.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] The first samples of ARM silicon worked properly when first received and tested on 26 April 1985.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Known as ARM1, these versions ran at 6 MHz.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] The first ARM application was as a second processor for the BBC Micro, where it helped in developing simulation software to finish development of the support chips (VIDC, IOC, MEMC), and sped up the CAD software used in ARM2 development.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Wilson subsequently rewrote BBC BASIC in ARM assembly language.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] The in-depth knowledge gained from designing the instruction set enabled the code to be very dense, making ARM BBC BASIC an extremely good test for any ARM emulator.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] ARM Evaluations Systems featuring ARM1 CPUs and supplied as second processors for BBC Micro and Master machines, were made available from July 1986 under the Acorn OEM Products brand to developers and researchers.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] The A500 Second Processor, an additional ARM1 based BBC Micro and Master second processor, featured the ARM support chipset (VIDC, IOC, MEMC), was capable of producing video output and operating near independently of the host BBC Micro.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] The result of the simulations on the ARM1 boards led to the late 1986 introduction of the ARM2 design running at 8 MHz, and the early 1987 speed-bumped version at 10 to 12 MHz.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] A significant change in the underlying architecture was the addition of a Booth multiplier, whereas formerly multiplication had to be carried out in software.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Further, a new Fast Interrupt reQuest mode, FIQ for short, allowed registers 8 to 14 to be replaced as part of the interrupt itself.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] This meant FIQ requests did not have to save out their registers, further speeding interrupts.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] The first use of the ARM2 was in internal Acorn A500 development machines, and the Acorn Archimedes personal computer models A305, A310, and A440, launched on the 6th June 1987.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] According to the Dhrystone benchmark, the ARM2 was roughly seven times the performance of a typical 7 MHz 68000-based system like the Amiga or Macintosh SE.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] It was twice as fast as an Intel 80386 running at 16 MHz, and about the same speed as a multi-processor VAX-11/784 superminicomputer.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] The only systems that beat it were the Sun SPARC and MIPS R2000 RISC-based workstations.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Further, as the CPU was designed for high-speed I/O, it dispensed with many of the support chips seen in these machines; notably, it lacked any dedicated direct memory access (DMA) controller which was often found on workstations.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] The graphics system was also simplified based on the same set of underlying assumptions about memory and timing.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] The result was a dramatically simplified design, offering performance on par with expensive workstations but at a price point similar to contemporary desktops.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] The ARM2 featured a 32-bit data bus, 26-bit address space and 27 32-bit registers, of which 16 are accessible at any one time (including the PC).
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] The ARM2 had a transistor count of just 30,000, compared to Motorola's six-year-older 68000 model with around 68,000.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Much of this simplicity came from the lack of microcode, which represents about one-quarter to one-third of the 68000's transistors, and the lack of (like most CPUs of the day) a cache.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] This simplicity enabled the ARM2 to have a low power consumption and simpler thermal packaging by having fewer powered transistors.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Nevertheless, ARM2 offered better performance than the contemporary 1987 IBM PS/2 Model 50, which initially utilised an Intel 80286, offering 1.8 MIPS @ 10 MHz, and later in 1987, the 2 MIPS of the PS/2 70, with its Intel 386 DX @ 16 MHz.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] A successor, ARM3, was produced with a 4 KB cache, which further improved performance.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] The address bus was extended to 32 bits in the ARM6, but program code still had to lie within the first 64 MB of memory in 26-bit compatibility mode, due to the reserved bits for the status flags.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 1988, Sanyo became a worldwide second source for the ARM2 and associated chipset under an agreement with VLSI Technology.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] In the late 1980s, Apple Computer and VLSI Technology started working with Acorn on newer versions of the ARM core.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 1990, Acorn spun off the design team into a new company named Advanced RISC Machines Ltd., which became ARM Ltd. when its parent company, Arm Holdings plc, floated on the London Stock Exchange and Nasdaq in 1998.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] The new Apple–ARM work would eventually evolve into the ARM6, first released in early 1992.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Apple used the ARM6-based ARM610 as the basis for their Apple Newton PDA.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 1994, Acorn used the ARM610 as the main central processing unit (CPU) in their RiscPC computers.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] DEC licensed the ARMv4 architecture and produced the StrongARM.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] At 233 MHz, this CPU drew only one watt (newer versions draw far less).
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] This work was later passed to Intel as part of a lawsuit settlement, and Intel took the opportunity to supplement their i960 line with the StrongARM.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Intel later developed its own high performance implementation named XScale, which it has since sold to Marvell.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Transistor count of the ARM core remained essentially the same throughout these changes; ARM2 had 30,000 transistors, while ARM6 grew only to 35,000.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2005, about 98% of all mobile phones sold used at least one ARM processor.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2010, producers of chips based on ARM architectures reported shipments of 6.1 billion ARM-based processors, representing 95% of smartphones, 35% of digital televisions and set-top boxes, and 10% of mobile computers.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2011, the 32-bit ARM architecture was the most widely used architecture in mobile devices and the most popular 32-bit one in embedded systems.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2013, 10 billion were produced and "ARM-based chips are found in nearly 60 percent of the world's mobile devices".
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm Holdings's primary business is selling IP cores, which licensees use to create microcontrollers (MCUs), CPUs, and systems-on-chips based on those cores.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] The original design manufacturer combines the ARM core with other parts to produce a complete device, typically one that can be built in existing semiconductor fabrication plants (fabs) at low cost and still deliver substantial performance.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] The most successful implementation has been the ARM7TDMI with hundreds of millions sold.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Atmel has been a precursor design center in the ARM7TDMI-based embedded system.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] The ARM architectures used in smartphones, PDAs and other mobile devices range from ARMv5 to ARMv8-A.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2009, some manufacturers introduced netbooks based on ARM architecture CPUs, in direct competition with netbooks based on Intel Atom.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm Holdings offers a variety of licensing terms, varying in cost and deliverables.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm Holdings provides to all licensees an integratable hardware description of the ARM core as well as complete software development toolset (compiler, debugger, software development kit), and the right to sell manufactured silicon containing the ARM CPU.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] SoC packages integrating ARM's core designs include Nvidia Tegra's first three generations, CSR plc's Quatro family, ST-Ericsson's Nova and NovaThor, Silicon Labs's Precision32 MCU, Texas Instruments's OMAP products, Samsung's Hummingbird and Exynos products, Apple's A4, A5, and A5X, and NXP's i.MX.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Fabless licensees, who wish to integrate an ARM core into their own chip design, are usually only interested in acquiring a ready-to-manufacture verified semiconductor intellectual property core.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] For these customers, Arm Holdings delivers a gate netlist description of the chosen ARM core, along with an abstracted simulation model and test programs to aid design integration and verification.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] More ambitious customers, including integrated device manufacturers (IDM) and foundry operators, choose to acquire the processor IP in synthesizable RTL (Verilog) form.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] With the synthesizable RTL, the customer has the ability to perform architectural level optimisations and extensions.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] This allows the designer to achieve exotic design goals not otherwise possible with an unmodified netlist (high clock speed, very low power consumption, instruction set extensions, etc.).
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] While Arm Holdings does not grant the licensee the right to resell the ARM architecture itself, licensees may freely sell manufactured products such as chip devices, evaluation boards and complete systems.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Merchant foundries can be a special case; not only are they allowed to sell finished silicon containing ARM cores, they generally hold the right to re-manufacture ARM cores for other customers.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm Holdings prices its IP based on perceived value.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Lower performing ARM cores typically have lower licence costs than higher performing cores.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] In implementation terms, a synthesisable core costs more than a hard macro (blackbox) core.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Complicating price matters, a merchant foundry that holds an ARM licence, such as Samsung or Fujitsu, can offer fab customers reduced licensing costs.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] In exchange for acquiring the ARM core through the foundry's in-house design services, the customer can reduce or eliminate payment of ARM's upfront licence fee.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Compared to dedicated semiconductor foundries (such as TSMC and UMC) without in-house design services, Fujitsu/Samsung charge two- to three-times more per manufactured wafer.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] For low to mid volume applications, a design service foundry offers lower overall pricing (through subsidisation of the licence fee).
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] For high volume mass-produced parts, the long term cost reduction achievable through lower wafer pricing reduces the impact of ARM's NRE (non-recurring engineering) costs, making the dedicated foundry a better choice.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] In February 2016, ARM announced the Built on ARM Cortex Technology licence, often shortened to Built on Cortex (BoC) licence.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] This licence allows companies to partner with ARM and make modifications to ARM Cortex designs.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] These design modifications will not be shared with other companies.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] These semi-custom core designs also have brand freedom, for example Kryo 280.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Companies that are current licensees of Built on ARM Cortex Technology include Qualcomm.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Companies can also obtain an ARM *architectural licence* for designing their own CPU cores using the ARM instruction sets.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] These cores must comply fully with the ARM architecture.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Companies that have designed cores that implement an ARM architecture include Apple, AppliedMicro (now: Ampere Computing), Broadcom, Cavium (now: Marvell), Digital Equipment Corporation, Intel, Nvidia, Qualcomm, Samsung Electronics, Fujitsu, and NUVIA Inc.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] On 16 July 2019, ARM announced ARM Flexible Access.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] ARM Flexible Access provides unlimited access to included ARM intellectual property (IP) for development.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Per product licence fees are required once a customer reaches foundry tapeout or prototyping.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] 75% of ARM's most recent IP over the last two years are included in ARM Flexible Access.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] ARMv3 included a compatibility mode to support the 26-bit addresses of earlier versions of the architecture.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] This compatibility mode is *optional* in ARMv4, and removed entirely in ARMv5.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm provides a list of vendors who implement ARM cores in their design (application specific standard products (ASSP), microprocessor and microcontrollers).
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] ARM cores are used in a number of products, particularly PDAs and smartphones.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Some computing examples are Microsoft's first generation Surface, Surface 2 and Pocket PC devices (following 2002), Apple's iPads, and Asus's Eee Pad Transformer tablet computers, and several Chromebook laptops.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] Others include Apple's iPhone smartphones and iPod portable media players, Canon PowerShot digital cameras, Nintendo Switch hybrid, the Wii security processor and 3DS handheld game consoles, and TomTom turn-by-turn navigation systems.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2005, Arm took part in the development of Manchester University's computer SpiNNaker, which used ARM cores to simulate the human brain.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p01] ARM chips are also used in Raspberry Pi, BeagleBoard, BeagleBone, PandaBoard, and other single-board computers, because they are very small, inexpensive, and consume very little power.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The 32-bit ARM architecture (**ARM32**), such as **ARMv7-A** (implementing AArch32; see section on Armv8-A for more on it), was the most widely used architecture in mobile devices as of 2011.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Although the architecture profiles were first defined for ARMv7, ARM subsequently defined the ARMv6-M architecture (used by the Cortex M0/M0+/M1) as a subset of the ARMv7-M profile with fewer instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] 26-bit addressing - obsolete as of June 2000.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Multiply and multiply-accumulate instructions; coprocessor support - all variants obsolete as of June 2000.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] 32-bit addressing - all variants obsolete as of July 2005.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] , the former of which supports the 32-bit ARM instruction set, called A32, and the Thumb-2 instruction set, called T32, and the latter of which supports a new instruction set with 32 64-bit registers, called A64.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Except in the M-profile, the 32-bit ARM architecture specifies several CPU modes, depending on the implemented architecture features.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] At any moment in time, the CPU can be in only one mode, but it can switch modes due to external events (interrupts) or programmatically.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The original ARM implementation was hardwired without microcode, like the much simpler 8-bit 6502 processor used in prior Acorn microcomputers.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM includes integer arithmetic operations for add, subtract, and multiply; some versions of the architecture also support divide operations.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM supports 32-bit × 32-bit multiplies with either a 32-bit result or 64-bit result, though Cortex-M0 / M0+ / M1 cores do not support 64-bit results.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Some ARM cores also support 16-bit × 16-bit and 32-bit × 16-bit multiplies.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Registers R0 through R7 are the same across all CPU modes; they are never banked.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Registers R8 through R12 are the same across all CPU modes except FIQ mode.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] FIQ mode has its own distinct R8 through R12 registers.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] R13 and R14 are banked across all privileged CPU modes except system mode.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] That is, each mode that can be entered because of an exception has its own R13 and R14.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] These registers generally contain the stack pointer and the return address from function calls, respectively.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Current Program Status Register (CPSR) has the following 32 bits.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Almost every ARM instruction has a conditional execution feature called predication, which is implemented with a 4-bit condition code selector (the predicate).
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] To allow for unconditional execution, one of the four-bit codes causes the instruction to be always executed.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Most other CPU architectures only have condition codes on branch instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Though the predicate takes up four of the 32 bits in an instruction code, and thus cuts down significantly on the encoding bits available for displacements in memory access instructions, it avoids branch instructions when generating code for small `if` statements.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Apart from eliminating the branch instructions themselves, this preserves the fetch/decode/execute pipeline at the cost of only one cycle per skipped instruction.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] An algorithm that provides a good example of conditional execution is the subtraction-based Euclidean algorithm for computing the greatest common divisor.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] which avoids the branches around the `then` and `else` clauses.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] If `r0` and `r1` are equal then neither of the `SUB` instructions will be executed, eliminating the need for a conditional branch to implement the `while` check at the top of the loop, for example had `SUBLE` (less than or equal) been used.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] One of the ways that Thumb code provides a more dense encoding is to remove the four-bit selector from non-branch instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] This results in the typical ARM program being denser than expected with fewer memory accesses; thus the pipeline is used more efficiently.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The ARM processor also has features rarely seen in other RISC architectures, such as PC-relative addressing (indeed, on the 32-bit ARM the PC is one of its 16 registers) and pre- and post-increment addressing modes.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The ARM instruction set has increased over time.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Some early ARM processors (before ARM7TDMI), for example, have no instruction to store a two-byte quantity.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The ARM7 and earlier implementations have a three-stage pipeline; the stages being fetch, decode, and execute.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Higher-performance designs, such as the ARM9, have deeper pipelines: Cortex-A8 has thirteen stages.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Additional implementation changes for higher performance include a faster adder and more extensive branch prediction logic.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The difference between the ARM7DI and ARM7DMI cores, for example, was an improved multiplier; hence the added "M".
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The ARM architecture (pre-Armv8) provides a non-intrusive way of extending the instruction set using "coprocessors" that can be addressed using MCR, MRC, MRRC, MCRR, and similar instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The coprocessor space is divided logically into 16 coprocessors with numbers from 0 to 15, coprocessor 15 (cp15) being reserved for some typical control functions like managing the caches and MMU operation on processors that have one.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] In ARM-based machines, peripheral devices are usually attached to the processor by mapping their physical registers into ARM memory space, into the coprocessor space, or by connecting to another device (a bus) that in turn attaches to the processor.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Coprocessor accesses have lower latency, so some peripherals—for example, an XScale interrupt controller—are accessible in both ways: through memory and through coprocessors.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] In other cases, chip designers only integrate hardware using the coprocessor mechanism.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] For example, an image processing engine might be a small ARM7TDMI core combined with a coprocessor that has specialised operations to support a specific set of HDTV transcoding primitives.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] All modern ARM processors include hardware debugging facilities, allowing software debuggers to perform operations such as halting, stepping, and breakpointing of code starting from reset.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] These facilities are built using JTAG support, though some newer cores optionally support ARM's own two-wire "SWD" protocol.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] In ARM7TDMI cores, the "D" represented JTAG debug support, and the "I" represented presence of an "EmbeddedICE" debug module.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] For ARM7 and ARM9 core generations, EmbeddedICE over JTAG was a de facto debug standard, though not architecturally guaranteed.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The ARMv7 architecture defines basic debug facilities at an architectural level.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] These include breakpoints, watchpoints and instruction execution in a "Debug Mode"; similar facilities were also available with EmbeddedICE.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Both "halt mode" and "monitor" mode debugging are supported.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The actual transport mechanism used to access the debug facilities is not architecturally specified, but implementations generally include JTAG support.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] There is a separate ARM "CoreSight" debug architecture, which is not architecturally required by ARMv7 processors.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Debug Access Port (DAP) is an implementation of an ARM Debug Interface.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] There are two different supported implementations, the Serial Wire JTAG Debug Port (SWJ-DP) and the Serial Wire Debug Port (SW-DP).
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] CMSIS-DAP is a standard interface that describes how various debugging software on a host PC can communicate over USB to firmware running on a hardware debugger, which in turn talks over SWD or JTAG to a CoreSight-enabled ARM Cortex CPU.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] To improve the ARM architecture for digital signal processing and multimedia applications, DSP instructions were added to the instruction set.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] These are signified by an "E" in the name of the ARMv5TE and ARMv5TEJ architectures.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The new instructions are common in digital signal processor (DSP) architectures.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] They include variations on signed multiply–accumulate, saturated add and subtract, and count leading zeros.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] First introduced in 1999, this extension of the core instruction set contrasted with ARM's earlier DSP coprocessor known as Piccolo, which employed a distinct, incompatible instruction set whose execution involved a separate program counter.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Piccolo instructions employed a distinct register file of sixteen 32-bit registers, with some instructions combining registers for use as 48-bit accumulators and other instructions addressing 16-bit half-registers.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Some instructions were able to operate on two such 16-bit values in parallel.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Communication with the Piccolo register file involved *load to Piccolo* and *store from Piccolo* coprocessor instructions via two buffers of eight 32-bit entries.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Described as reminiscent of other approaches, notably Hitachi's SH-DSP and Motorola's 68356, Piccolo did not employ dedicated local memory and relied on the bandwidth of the ARM core for DSP operand retrieval, impacting concurrent performance.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Piccolo's distinct instruction set also proved not to be a "good compiler target".
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Introduced in the ARMv6 architecture, this was a precursor to Advanced SIMD, also named Neon.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Jazelle DBX (Direct Bytecode eXecution) is a technique that allows Java bytecode to be executed directly in the ARM architecture as a third execution state (and instruction set) alongside the existing ARM and Thumb-mode.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Support for this state is signified by the "J" in the ARMv5TEJ architecture, and in ARM9EJ-S and ARM7EJ-S core names.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Support for this state is required starting in ARMv6 (except for the ARMv7-M profile), though newer cores only include a trivial implementation that provides no hardware acceleration.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] To improve compiled code density, processors since the ARM7TDMI (released in 1994) have featured the *Thumb* compressed instruction set, which have their own state.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] (The "T" in "TDMI" indicates the Thumb feature.) When in this state, the processor executes the Thumb instruction set, a compact 16-bit encoding for a subset of the ARM instruction set.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Most of the Thumb instructions are directly mapped to normal ARM instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The space saving comes from making some of the instruction operands implicit and limiting the number of possibilities compared to the ARM instructions executed in the ARM instruction set state.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] In Thumb, the 16-bit opcodes have less functionality.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] For example, only branches can be conditional, and many opcodes are restricted to accessing only half of all of the CPU's general-purpose registers.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The shorter opcodes give improved code density overall, even though some operations require extra instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] In situations where the memory port or bus width is constrained to less than 32 bits, the shorter Thumb opcodes allow increased performance compared with 32-bit ARM code, as less program code may need to be loaded into the processor over the constrained memory bandwidth.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Unlike processor architectures with variable length (16- or 32-bit) instructions, such as the Cray-1 and Hitachi SuperH, the ARM and Thumb instruction sets exist independently of each other.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Embedded hardware, such as the Game Boy Advance, typically have a small amount of RAM accessible with a full 32-bit datapath; the majority is accessed via a 16-bit or narrower secondary datapath.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] In this situation, it usually makes sense to compile Thumb code and hand-optimise a few of the most CPU-intensive sections using full 32-bit ARM instructions, placing these wider instructions into the 32-bit bus accessible memory.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The first processor with a Thumb instruction decoder was the ARM7TDMI.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] All processors supporting 32-bit instruction sets, starting with ARM9, and including XScale, have included a Thumb instruction decoder.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] It includes instructions adopted from the Hitachi SuperH (1992), which was licensed by ARM.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM's smallest processor families (Cortex M0 and M1) implement only the 16-bit Thumb instruction set for maximum performance in lowest cost applications.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM processors that don't support 32-bit addressing also omit Thumb.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Thumb-2 extends the Thumb instruction set with bit-field manipulation, table branches and conditional execution.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] At the same time, the ARM instruction set was extended to maintain equivalent functionality in both instruction sets.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] A new "Unified Assembly Language" (UAL) supports generation of either Thumb or ARM instructions from the same source code; versions of Thumb seen on ARMv7 processors are essentially as capable as ARM code (including the ability to write interrupt handlers).
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] This requires a bit of care, and use of a new "IT" (if-then) instruction, which permits up to four successive instructions to execute based on a tested condition, or on its inverse.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] When compiling into ARM code, this is ignored, but when compiling into Thumb it generates an actual instruction.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] All ARMv7 chips support the Thumb instruction set.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] All chips in the Cortex-A series that support ARMv7, all Cortex-R series, and all ARM11 series support both "ARM instruction set state" and "Thumb instruction set state", while chips in the Cortex-M series support only the Thumb instruction set.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] New features provided by ThumbEE include automatic null pointer checks on every load and store instruction, an instruction to perform an array bounds check, and special instructions that call a handler.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] In addition, because it utilises Thumb-2 technology, ThumbEE provides access to registers r8–r15 (where the Jazelle/DBX Java VM state is held).
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Handlers are small sections of frequently called code, commonly used to implement high level languages, such as allocating memory for a new object.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] These changes come from repurposing a handful of opcodes, and knowing the core is in the new ThumbEE state.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] On 23 November 2011, Arm deprecated any use of the ThumbEE instruction set, and Armv8 removes support for ThumbEE.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Some devices such as the ARM Cortex-A8 have a cut-down *VFPLite* module instead of a full VFP module, and require roughly ten times more clock cycles per float operation.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Pre-Armv8 architecture implemented floating-point/SIMD with the coprocessor interface.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Other floating-point and/or SIMD units found in ARM-based processors using the coprocessor interface include FPA, FPE, iwMMXt, some of which were implemented in software by trapping but could have been implemented in hardware.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] They provide some of the same functionality as VFP but are not opcode-compatible with it.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] FPA10 also provides extended precision, but implements correct rounding (required by IEEE 754) only in single precision.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] An optional extension to the ARM instruction set in the ARMv5TE, ARMv5TEJ and ARMv6 architectures.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Implemented on most Cortex-A8 and A9 ARMv7 processors.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] It is backward-compatible with VFPv2, except that it cannot trap floating-point exceptions.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] VFPv3 has 32 64-bit FPU registers as standard, adds VCVT instructions to convert between scalar, float and double, adds immediate mode to VMOV such that constants can be loaded into FPU registers.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] As above, but with only 16 64-bit FPU registers.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Implemented on Cortex-A12 and A15 ARMv7 processors, Cortex-A7 optionally has VFPv4-D32 in the case of an FPU with Neon.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] As above, but it has only 16 64-bit FPU registers.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Implemented on Cortex-A5 and A7 processors in the case of an FPU without Neon.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Implemented on Cortex-M7 when single and double-precision floating-point core option exists.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] In Debian Linux and derivatives such as Ubuntu and Linux Mint, **armhf** (**ARM hard float**) refers to the ARMv7 architecture including the additional VFP3-D16 floating-point hardware extension (and Thumb-2) above.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Software packages and cross-compiler tools use the armhf vs. arm/armel suffixes to differentiate.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The *Advanced SIMD* extension (also known as *Neon* or "MPE" Media Processing Engine) is a combined 64- and 128-bit SIMD instruction set that provides standardised acceleration for media and signal processing applications.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Neon is included in all Cortex-A8 devices, but is optional in Cortex-A9 devices.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Neon can execute MP3 audio decoding on CPUs running at 10 MHz, and can run the GSM adaptive multi-rate (AMR) speech codec at 13 MHz.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] It features a comprehensive instruction set, separate register files, and independent execution hardware.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Neon supports 8-, 16-, 32-, and 64-bit integer and single-precision (32-bit) floating-point data and SIMD operations for handling audio and video processing as well as graphics and gaming processing.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] In Neon, the SIMD supports up to 16 operations at the same time.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Neon hardware shares the same floating-point registers as used in VFP.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Devices such as the ARM Cortex-A8 and Cortex-A9 support 128-bit vectors, but will execute with 64 bits at a time, whereas some more powerful CPUs such as Cortex-A15 can execute 128 bits at a time.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] A quirk of Neon in Armv7 devices is that it flushes all subnormal numbers to zero, and as a result the GCC compiler will not use it unless `-funsafe-math-optimizations`, which allows losing denormals, is turned on.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] "Enhanced" Neon defined since Armv8 does not have this quirk, but as of GCC 8.2 the same flag is still required to enable Neon instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] On the other hand, GCC does consider Neon safe on AArch64 for Armv8.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] ProjectNe10 is ARM's first open-source project (from its inception; while they acquired an older project, now named Mbed TLS).
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Ne10 library is a set of common, useful functions written in both Neon and C (for compatibility).
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The library was created to allow developers to use Neon optimisations without learning Neon, but it also serves as a set of highly optimised Neon intrinsic and assembly code examples for common DSP, arithmetic, and image processing routines.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Helium is the M-Profile Vector Extension (MVE).
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] It adds more than 150 scalar and vector instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Security Extensions, marketed as TrustZone Technology, is in ARMv6KZ and later application profile architectures.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] It provides a low-cost alternative to adding another dedicated security core to an SoC, by providing two virtual processors backed by hardware based access control.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] This lets the application core switch between two states, referred to as *worlds* (to reduce confusion with other names for capability domains), to prevent information leaking from the more trusted world (the *Secure world*) to the less trusted world (the *Normal world*).
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] This world switch is generally orthogonal to all other capabilities of the processor, thus each world can operate independently of the other while using the same core.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Memory and peripherals are then made aware of the operating world of the core and may use this to provide access control to secrets and code on the device.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Typically, a rich operating system is run in the less trusted world, with smaller security-specialised code in the more trusted world, aiming to reduce the attack surface.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Typical applications include DRM functionality for controlling the use of media on ARM-based devices, and preventing any unapproved use of the device.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] In practice, since the specific implementation details of proprietary TrustZone implementations have not been publicly disclosed for review, it is unclear what level of assurance is provided for a given threat model, but they are not immune from attack.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Open Virtualization is an open source implementation of the trusted world architecture for TrustZone.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] AMD has licensed and incorporated TrustZone technology into its Secure Processor Technology.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] AMD's APUs include a Cortex-A5 processor for handling secure processing, which is enabled in some, but not all products.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] In fact, the Cortex-A5 TrustZone core had been included in earlier AMD products, but was not enabled due to time constraints.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Samsung Knox uses TrustZone for purposes such as detecting modifications to the kernel, storing certificates and attestating keys.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Security Extension, marketed as TrustZone for Armv8-M Technology, was introduced in the Armv8-M architecture.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] While containing similar concepts to TrustZone for Armv8-A, it has a different architectural design, as world switching is performed using branch instructions instead of using exceptions.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] It also supports safe interleaved interrupt handling from either world regardless of the current security state.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Together these features provide low latency calls to the secure world and responsive interrupt handling.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM provides a reference stack of secure world code in the form of Trusted Firmware for M and PSA Certified.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] As of ARMv6, the ARM architecture supports no-execute page protection, which is referred to as *XN*, for *eXecute Never*.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Large Physical Address Extension (LPAE), which extends the physical address size from 32 bits to 40 bits, was added to the Armv7-A architecture in 2011.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The physical address size may be even larger in processors based on the 64-bit (Armv8-A) architecture.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] For example, it is 44 bits in Cortex-A75 and Cortex-A65AE.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The **Armv8-R** and **Armv8-M** architectures, announced after the Armv8-A architecture, share some features with Armv8-A.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] However, Armv8-M does not include any 64-bit AArch64 instructions, and Armv8-R originally did not include any AArch64 instructions; those instructions were added to Armv8-R later.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Armv8.1-M architecture, announced in February 2019, is an enhancement of the Armv8-M architecture.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Announced in October 2011, **Armv8-A** (often called ARMv8 while the Armv8-R is also available) represents a fundamental change to the ARM architecture.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] It supports two *Execution states*: a 64-bit state named *AArch64* and a 32-bit state named *AArch32*.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] In the AArch64 state, a new 64-bit *A64* instruction set is supported; in the AArch32 state, two instruction sets are supported: the original 32-bit instruction set, named *A32*, and the 32-bit Thumb-2 instruction set, named *T32*.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] AArch32 provides user-space compatibility with Armv7-A.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The processor state can change on an Exception level change; this allows 32-bit applications to be executed in AArch32 state under a 64-bit OS whose kernel executes in AArch64 state, and allows a 32-bit OS to run in AArch32 state under the control of a 64-bit hypervisor running in AArch64 state.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Apple was the first to release an Armv8-A compatible core in a consumer product (Apple A7 in iPhone 5S).
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The first Armv8-A SoC from Samsung is the Exynos 5433 used in the Galaxy Note 4, which features two clusters of four Cortex-A57 and Cortex-A53 cores in a big.LITTLE configuration; but it will run only in AArch32 mode.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] To both AArch32 and AArch64, Armv8-A makes VFPv3/v4 and advanced SIMD (Neon) standard.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] AArch64 was introduced in Armv8-A and its subsequent revision.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] AArch64 is not included in the 32-bit Armv8-R and Armv8-M architectures.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Announced in March 2021, the updated architecture places a focus on secure execution and compartmentalisation.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The first ARMv9-A processors were released later that year, including the Cortex-A510, Cortex-A710 and Cortex-X2.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Arm SystemReady is a compliance program that helps ensure the interoperability of an operating system on Arm-based hardware from datacenter servers to industrial edge and IoT devices.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The key building blocks of the program are the specifications for minimum hardware and firmware requirements that the operating systems and hypervisors can rely upon.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] These specifications are co-developed by Arm and its partners in the System Architecture Advisory Committee (SystemArchAC).
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Architecture Compliance Suite (ACS) is the test tools that help to check the compliance of these specifications.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Arm SystemReady Requirements Specification documents the requirements of the certifications.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] This program was introduced by Arm in 2020 at the first DevSummit event.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Its predecessor Arm ServerReady was introduced in 2018 at the Arm TechCon event.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] PSA Certified, formerly named Platform Security Architecture, is an architecture-agnostic security framework and evaluation scheme.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] It is intended to help secure Internet of things (IoT) devices built on system-on-a-chip (SoC) processors.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] It was introduced to increase security where a full trusted execution environment is too large or complex.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The architecture was introduced by Arm in 2017 at the annual TechCon event.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Although the scheme is architecture agnostic, it was first implemented on Arm Cortex-M processor cores intended for microcontroller use.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] PSA Certified includes freely available threat models and security analyses that demonstrate the process for deciding on security features in common IoT products.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] It also provides freely downloadable application programming interface (API) packages, architectural specifications, open-source firmware implementations, and related test suites.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Following the development of the architecture security framework in 2017, the PSA Certified assurance scheme launched two years later at Embedded World in 2019.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] PSA Certified offers a multi-level security evaluation scheme for chip vendors, OS providers and IoT device makers.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Embedded World presentation introduced chip vendors to Level 1 Certification.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] A draft of Level 2 protection was presented at the same time.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Level 2 certification became a usable standard in February 2020.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The certification was created by PSA Joint Stakeholders to enable a security-by-design approach for a diverse set of IoT products.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] PSA Certified specifications are implementation and architecture agnostic, as a result they can be applied to any chip, software or device.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The certification also removes industry fragmentation for IoT product manufacturers and developers.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The first 32-bit ARM-based personal computer, the Acorn Archimedes, was originally intended to run an ambitious operating system called ARX.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] The machines shipped with RISC OS, which was also used on later ARM-based systems from Acorn and other vendors.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-architecture-family-p02] Some early Acorn machines were also able to run a Unix port called RISC iX.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] The **ARM Cortex-M** is a group of 32-bit RISC ARM processor cores licensed by ARM Limited.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] These cores are optimized for low-cost and energy-efficient integrated circuits, which have been embedded in tens of billions of consumer devices.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] Though they are most often the main component of microcontroller chips, sometimes they are embedded inside other types of chips too.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M family consists of Cortex-M0, Cortex-M0+, Cortex-M1, Cortex-M3, Cortex-M4, Cortex-M7, Cortex-M23, Cortex-M33, Cortex-M35P, Cortex-M52, Cortex-M55, Cortex-M85.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] A floating-point unit (FPU) option is available for Cortex-M4 / M7 / M33 / M35P / M52 / M55 / M85 cores, and when included in the silicon these cores are sometimes known as "Cortex-MxF", where 'x' is the core variant.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] The ARM Cortex-M family are ARM microprocessor cores that are designed for use in microcontrollers, ASICs, ASSPs, FPGAs, and SoCs.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] Cortex-M cores are commonly used as dedicated microcontroller chips, but also are "hidden" inside of SoC chips as power management controllers, I/O controllers, system controllers, touch screen controllers, smart battery controllers, and sensor controllers.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] The main difference from Cortex-A cores is that Cortex-M cores have no memory management unit (MMU) for virtual memory, considered essential for "full-fledged" operating systems.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] Cortex-M programs instead run bare metal or on one of the many real-time operating systems which support a Cortex-M.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] Though 8-bit microcontrollers were very popular in the past, Cortex-M has slowly been chipping away at the 8-bit market as the prices of low-end Cortex-M chips have moved downward.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] Cortex-M have become a popular replacements for 8-bit chips in applications that benefit from 32-bit math operations, and replacing older legacy ARM cores such as ARM7 and ARM9.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] In particular, the embedded wear-leveling controller inside most SD cards or flash drives is a (8-bit) 8051 microcontroller or ARM CPU.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] ARM Limited neither manufactures nor sells CPU devices based on its own designs, but rather licenses the processor architecture to interested parties.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] Arm offers a variety of licensing terms, varying in cost and deliverables.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] To all licensees, Arm provides an integratable hardware description of the ARM core, as well as complete software development toolset and the right to sell manufactured silicon containing the ARM CPU.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] Integrated Device Manufacturers (IDM) receive the ARM Processor IP as synthesizable RTL (written in Verilog).
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] In this form, they have the ability to perform architectural level optimizations and extensions.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] This allows the manufacturer to achieve custom design goals, such as higher clock speed, very low power consumption, instruction set extensions (including floating point), optimizations for size, debug support, etc.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] To determine which components have been included in a particular ARM CPU chip, consult the manufacturer datasheet and related documentation.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] The architectures are binary instruction upward compatible from ARMv6-M to ARMv7-M to ARMv7E-M.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] Binary instructions available for the Cortex-M0 / Cortex-M0+ / Cortex-M1 can execute without modification on the Cortex-M3 / Cortex-M4 / Cortex-M7.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] Binary instructions available for the Cortex-M3 can execute without modification on the Cortex-M4 / Cortex-M7 / Cortex-M33 / Cortex-M35P.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] Only Thumb-1 and Thumb-2 instruction sets are supported in Cortex-M architectures; the legacy 32-bit ARM instruction set isn't supported.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] All Cortex-M cores implement a common subset of instructions that consists of most Thumb-1, some Thumb-2, including a 32-bit result multiply.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0 / Cortex-M0+ / Cortex-M1 / Cortex-M23 were designed to create the smallest silicon die, thus having the fewest instructions of the Cortex-M family.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0 / M0+ / M1 include Thumb-1 instructions, except new instructions (CBZ, CBNZ, IT) which were added in ARMv7-M architecture.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0 / M0+ / M1 include a minor subset of Thumb-2 instructions (BL, DMB, DSB, ISB, MRS, MSR).
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M3 / M4 / M7 / M33 / M35P have all base Thumb-1 and Thumb-2 instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M3 adds three Thumb-1 instructions, all Thumb-2 instructions, hardware integer divide, and saturation arithmetic instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M4 adds DSP instructions and an optional single-precision floating-point unit (VFPv4-SP).
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M7 adds an optional double-precision FPU (VFPv5).
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M23 / M33 / M35P / M52 / M55 / M85 add TrustZone instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] The 16-bit Thumb-1 instruction set has evolved over time since it was first released in the legacy ARM7T cores with the ARMv4T architecture.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] New Thumb-1 instructions were added as each legacy ARMv5 / ARMv6 / ARMv6T2 architectures were released.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0 core is optimized for small silicon die size and use in the lowest price chips.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0+ is an optimized superset of the Cortex-M0.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0+ has complete instruction set compatibility with the Cortex-M0 thus allowing the use of the same compiler and debug tools.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0+ pipeline was reduced from 3 to 2 stages, which lowers the power usage and increases performance (higher average IPC due to branches taking one fewer cycle).
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] In addition to debug features in the existing Cortex-M0, a silicon option can be added to the Cortex-M0+ called the Micro Trace Buffer (MTB) which provides a simple instruction trace buffer.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0+ also received Cortex-M3 and Cortex-M4 features, which can be added as silicon options, such as the memory protection unit (MPU) and the vector table relocation.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] The smallest ARM microcontrollers are of the Cortex-M0+ type (as of 2014, smallest at 1.6 mm by 2 mm in a chip-scale package is Kinetis KL03).
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M1 is an optimized core especially designed to be loaded into FPGA chips.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] Conceptually the Cortex-M4 is a Cortex-M3 plus DSP instructions, and optional floating-point unit (FPU).
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] A core with an FPU is known as Cortex-M4F.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M7 is a high-performance core with almost double the power efficiency of the older Cortex-M4.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] It features a 6-stage superscalar pipeline with branch prediction and an optional floating-point unit capable of single-precision and optionally double-precision operations.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] The instruction and data buses have been enlarged to 64-bit wide over the previous 32-bit buses.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] If a core contains an FPU, it is known as a Cortex-M7F, otherwise it is a Cortex-M7.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M23 core was announced in October 2016 and based on the ARMv8-M architecture that was previously announced in November 2015.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] Conceptually the Cortex-M23 is similar to a Cortex-M0+ plus integer divide instructions and TrustZone security features, and also has a 2-stage instruction pipeline.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M33 core was announced in October 2016 and based on the ARMv8-M architecture that was previously announced in November 2015.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] Conceptually the Cortex-M33 is similar to a cross of Cortex-M4 and Cortex-M23, and also has a 3-stage instruction pipeline.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M35P core was announced in May 2018 and based on the Armv8-M architecture.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] It is conceptually a Cortex-M33 core with a new instruction cache, plus new tamper-resistant hardware concepts borrowed from the ARM SecurCore family, and configurable parity and ECC features.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] Currently, information about the Cortex-M35P is limited, because its *Technical Reference Manual* and *Generic User Guide* haven't been released yet.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M52 core was announced in November 2023 and based on the Armv8.1-M architecture.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] Conceptually, it can be seen as a cross between the Cortex-M33 and the Cortex-M55.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] Key differences are that its Helium co-processor is single beat (the M55 is dual beat), and it has a 32-bit main bus similar to the M33 to ease transition of applications.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M55 core was announced in February 2020 and based on the Armv8.1-M architecture.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] It has a 4 or 5 stage instruction pipeline.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M85 core was announced in April 2022 and based on the Armv8.1-M architecture.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] The documentation for ARM chips is extensive.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] In the past, 8-bit microcontroller documentation would typically fit in a single document, but as microcontrollers have evolved, so has everything required to support them.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] A documentation package for ARM chips typically consists of a collection of documents from the IC manufacturer as well as the CPU core vendor (ARM Limited).
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] IC manufacturer datasheet for the exact physical chip.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] IC manufacturer reference manual that describes common peripherals and aspects of a physical chip family.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] IC manufacturers have additional documents, such as: evaluation board user manuals, application notes, getting started guides, software library documents, errata, and more.
[src:arm-riscv/arm-cortex-m] See External links section for links to official Arm documents.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] In computing, **endianness** is the order in which bytes within a *word* data type are transmitted over a data communication medium or addressed in computer memory, counting only byte significance compared to earliness.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Endianness is primarily expressed as **big-endian** (**BE**) or **little-endian** (**LE**).
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Computers store information in various-sized groups of binary bits.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Each group is assigned a number, called its *address*, that the computer uses to access that data.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] On most modern computers, the smallest data group with an address is eight bits long, and is called a *byte*.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Larger groups comprise two or more bytes; for example, a *word* often contains 32 bits or 64 bits.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] There are two principal ways a computer could number the individual bytes in a larger group, starting at either end.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] A big-endian system stores the most significant byte of a word at the smallest memory address and the least significant byte at the largest.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] A little-endian system, in contrast, stores the least-significant byte at the smallest address.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Of the two, big-endian is thus closer to the way the digits of numbers are written left-to-right in English, with the most significant digit first, comparing digits to bytes and assuming addresses increase from left to right.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Both types of endianness are in widespread use in digital electronic engineering.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] The initial choice of endianness of a new design is often arbitrary, but later technology revisions and updates perpetuate the existing endianness to maintain backward compatibility.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Big-endianness is the dominant ordering in networking protocols, such as in the Internet protocol suite, where it is referred to as *network order*, transmitting the most significant byte first.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Conversely, little-endianness is the dominant ordering for processor architectures (x86, most ARM implementations, base RISC-V implementations) and their associated memory.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] File formats can use either ordering; some formats use a mixture of both or contain an indicator of which ordering is used throughout the file.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Endianness is primarily expressed as **big-endian** (BE) or **little-endian** (LE), terms introduced by Danny Cohen in an Internet Experiment Note published in 1980.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Cohen borrowed the terms from an absurd episode in the satirical novel *Gulliver's Travels* by Jonathan Swift.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] In the imaginary land of Lilliput, scholars are fiercely divided by a never-ending debate over how correctly to break the shell of a boiled egg.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Those who insist on breaking the big end of the shell are Big-Endians, while their opponents who break the opposite end of the shell are Little-Endians.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Computer memory consists of a sequence of storage cells (smallest addressable units); in machines that support byte addressing, those units are called *bytes*.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Each byte is identified and accessed in hardware and software by its memory address.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] If the total number of bytes in memory is *n*, then addresses are enumerated from 0 to *n* − 1.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Computer programs often use data structures or fields that may consist of more data than can be stored in one byte.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] In the context of this article, where its type cannot be arbitrarily complicated, a *field* consists of a consecutive sequence of bytes and represents a *simple data value* which, at least potentially, can be manipulated by *one* single hardware instruction.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] On most systems, the address of a multi-byte simple data value is the address of its first byte (the byte with the lowest address).
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] There are exceptions to this rule – for example, the Add instruction of the IBM 1401 addresses variable-length fields at their low-order (highest-addressed) position with their lengths being defined by a word mark set at their high-order (lowest-addressed) position.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] When an operation such as addition is performed, the processor begins at the low-order positions at the high addresses of the two fields and works its way down to the high-order.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Another important attribute of a byte being part of a *field* is its *significance*.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] These attributes of the parts of a field play an important role in the sequence the bytes are accessed by the computer hardware, more precisely: by the low-level algorithms contributing to the results of a computer instruction.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Positional number systems (mostly base 2, or less often base 10) are the predominant way of representing and particularly of manipulating integer data by computers.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] In pure form, this is valid for moderately sized non-negative integers, e.g., of C data type `unsigned`.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] In such a number system, the *value* of a digit that contributes to the whole number is determined not only by its value as a single digit, but also by the position it holds in the complete number, called its significance.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] In *big-endian* and *little-endian*, the *end* is the extremity where the *big* or *little* significance is written in the location indexed by the lowest memory address.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] When character (text) strings are to be compared with one another, e.g., in order to support some mechanism like sorting, this is very frequently done lexicographically where a single positional element (character) also has a positional value.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Lexicographical comparison means almost everywhere: first character ranks highest, as in the telephone book.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Almost all machines that can do this using a single instruction are big-endian or at least mixed-endian.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Integer numbers written as text are always represented most significant digit first in memory, which is similar to big-endian, independently of text direction.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] When memory bytes are printed sequentially from left to right (e.g., in a hex dump), little-endian representation of integers has the significance decreasing from right to left.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] In other words, it appears backwards when visualized, which can be counterintuitive.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] This behavior arises, for example, in FourCC or similar techniques that involve packing characters into an integer, so that it becomes a sequence of specific characters in memory.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] For example, take the string "JOHN", stored in hexadecimal ASCII.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] On big-endian machines, the value appears left-to-right, coinciding with the correct string order for reading the result ("J O H N").
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] But on a little-endian machine, one would see "N H O J".
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Middle-endian machines complicate this even further; for example, on the PDP-11, a 32-bit float is stored as two 16-bit words "JO" "HN" in big-endian, with the characters in the 16-bit words being stored in little-endian, resulting in "O J N H".
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Byte-swapping consists of rearranging bytes to change endianness.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Many compilers provide built-ins that are likely to be compiled into native processor instructions (`bswap`/`movbe`), such as `__builtin_bswap32`.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Some CPU instruction sets provide native support for endian byte swapping, such as `bswap` (x86 — 486 and later, i960 — i960Jx and later), and `rev` (ARMv6 and later).
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Some compilers have built-in facilities for byte swapping.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] For example, GNU Fortran and the Intel Fortran Compiler both support the non-standard `CONVERT` specifier when opening a file, e.g.: `OPEN(unit, CONVERT='BIG_ENDIAN',...)`.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Other compilers have options for generating code that globally enables the conversion for all file IO operations.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] This permits the reuse of code on a system with the opposite endianness without code modification.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] For example, a 32-bit memory location with content `4A 00 00 00` can be read at the same address as either 8-bit (value = 4A), 16-bit (004A), 24-bit (00004A), or 32-bit (0000004A), all of which retain the same numeric value.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Although this little-endian property is rarely used directly by high-level programmers, it is occasionally employed by code optimizers as well as by assembly language programmers.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] While not allowed by C++, such type punning code is allowed as "implementation-defined" by the C11 standard and commonly used in code interacting with hardware.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Some operations in positional number systems have a natural or preferred order in which the elementary steps are to be executed.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] This order may affect their performance on small-scale byte-addressable processors and microcontrollers.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] However, high-performance processors usually fetch multi-byte operands from memory in the same amount of time they would have fetched a single byte, so the complexity of the hardware is not affected by the byte ordering.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Addition, subtraction, and multiplication start at the least significant digit position and propagate the carry to the subsequent more significant position.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] On most systems, the address of a multi-byte value is the address of its first byte (the byte with the lowest address).
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] The implementation of these operations is marginally simpler using little-endian machines, where this first byte contains the least significant digit.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Comparison and division start at the most significant digit and propagate a possible carry to the subsequent less significant digits.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] For fixed-length numerical values (typically of length 1,2,4,8,16), the implementation of these operations is marginally simpler on big-endian machines.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Some big-endian processors (e.g., the IBM System/360 and its successors) contain hardware instructions for lexicographically comparing varying-length character strings.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] The normal data transport by an assignment statement is, in principle, independent of the endianness of the processor.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Many historical and extant processors use a big-endian memory representation, either exclusively or as a design option.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] The IBM System/360 uses big-endian byte order, as do its successors System/370, ESA/390, and z/Architecture.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] The PDP-10 uses big-endian addressing for byte-oriented instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] The IBM Series/1 minicomputer uses big-endian byte order.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] The Motorola 6800 / 6801, the 6809 and the 68000 series of processors use the big-endian format.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Solely big-endian architectures include the IBM z/Architecture and OpenRISC.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] The PDP-11 minicomputer, however, uses little-endian byte order, as does its VAX successor.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] The Datapoint 2200 used simple bit-serial logic with little-endian to facilitate carry propagation.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] When Intel developed the 8008 microprocessor for Datapoint, they used little-endian for compatibility.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] However, as Intel was unable to deliver the 8008 in time, Datapoint used a medium-scale integration equivalent, but the little-endianness was retained in most Intel designs, including the MCS-48 and the 8086 and its x86 successors, including IA-32 and x86-64 processors.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] The MOS Technology 6502 family (including Western Design Center 65802 and 65C816), the Zilog Z80 (including Z180 and eZ80), the Altera Nios II, the Atmel AVR, the Andes Technology NDS32, the Qualcomm Hexagon, and many other processors and processor families are also little-endian.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] The Intel 8051, unlike other Intel processors, expects 16-bit addresses for LJMP and LCALL in big-endian format; however, xCALL instructions store the return address onto the stack in little-endian format.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Some instruction set architectures feature a setting which allows for switchable endianness in data fetches and stores, instruction fetches, or both; those instruction set architectures are referred to as *bi-endian*.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Architectures that support switchable endianness include PowerPC/Power ISA, SPARC V9, ARM versions 3 and above, DEC Alpha, MIPS, Intel i860, PA-RISC, SuperH SH-4, IA-64, C-Sky, and RISC-V.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] This feature can improve performance or simplify the logic of networking devices and software.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] The word *bi-endian*, when said of hardware, denotes the capability of the machine to compute or pass data in either endian format.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] IBM AIX and IBM i run in big-endian mode on bi-endian Power ISA; Linux originally ran in big-endian mode, but by 2019, IBM had transitioned to little-endian mode for Linux to ease the porting of Linux software from x86 to Power.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] SPARC has no relevant little-endian deployment, as both Oracle Solaris and Linux run in big-endian mode on bi-endian SPARC systems, and can be considered big-endian in practice.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] ARM, C-Sky, and RISC-V have no relevant big-endian deployments and can be considered little-endian in practice.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] The term *bi-endian* refers primarily to how a processor treats data accesses.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Instruction accesses (fetches of instruction words) on a given processor may still assume a fixed endianness, even if data accesses are fully bi-endian, though this is not always the case, such as on Intel's IA-64-based Itanium CPU, which allows both.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Some nominally bi-endian CPUs require motherboard help to fully switch endianness.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] In the absence of this unusual motherboard hardware, device driver software must write to different addresses to undo the incomplete transformation and also must perform a normal byte swap.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Some CPUs, such as many PowerPC processors intended for embedded use and almost all SPARC processors, allow per-page choice of endianness.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] SPARC processors since the late 1990s (SPARC v9 compliant processors) allow data endianness to be chosen with each individual instruction that loads from or stores to memory.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] The ARM architecture supports two big-endian modes, called *BE-8* and *BE-32*.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] CPUs up to ARMv5 only support BE-32 or word-invariant mode.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Here, any naturally aligned 32-bit access works like in little-endian mode, but access to a byte or 16-bit word is redirected to the corresponding address and unaligned access is not allowed.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] ARMv6 introduces BE-8 or byte-invariant mode, where access to a single byte works as in little-endian mode, but accessing a 16-bit, 32-bit or (starting with ARMv8) 64-bit word results in a byte swap of the data.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] This simplifies unaligned memory access as well as memory-mapped access to registers other than 32-bit.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Many processors have instructions to convert a word in a register to the opposite endianness, that is, they swap the order of the bytes in a 16-, 32- or 64-bit word.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Recent Intel x86 and x86-64 architecture CPUs have a MOVBE instruction (Intel Core since generation 4, after Atom), which fetches a big-endian format word from memory or writes a word into memory in big-endian format.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] These processors are otherwise thoroughly little-endian.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] There are also devices that use different formats in different places.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] For instance, the BQ27421 Texas Instruments battery gauge uses the little-endian format for its registers and the big-endian format for its random-access memory.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] SPARC historically used big-endian until version 9, which is bi-endian.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Similarly, early IBM POWER processors were big-endian, but the PowerPC and Power ISA descendants are now bi-endian.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] The ARM architecture was little-endian before version 3, when it became bi-endian.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Although many processors use little-endian storage for all types of data (integer, floating point), there are a number of hardware architectures where floating-point numbers are represented in big-endian form while integers are represented in little-endian form.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] There are ARM processors that have mixed-endian floating-point representation for double-precision numbers: each of the two 32-bit words is stored as little-endian, but the most significant word is stored first.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] VAX floating point stores little-endian 16-bit words in big-endian order.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Because there have been many floating-point formats with no network standard representation for them, the XDR standard uses big-endian IEEE 754 as its representation.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] It may therefore appear strange that the widespread IEEE 754 floating-point standard does not specify endianness.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Theoretically, this means that even standard IEEE floating-point data written by one machine might not be readable by another.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] However, on modern standard computers (i.e., implementing IEEE 754), one may safely assume that the endianness is the same for floating-point numbers as for integers, making the conversion straightforward regardless of data type.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Small embedded systems using special floating-point formats may be another matter, however.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Most instructions considered so far contain the size (lengths) of their operands within the operation code.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Frequently available operand lengths are 1, 2, 4, 8, or 16 bytes.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] But there are also architectures where the length of an operand may be held in a separate field of the instruction or with the operand itself, e.g., by means of a word mark.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Such an approach allows operand lengths up to 256 bytes or larger.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] The data types of such operands are character strings or BCD.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Machines able to manipulate such data with one instruction (e.g. compare, add) include the IBM 1401, 1410, 1620, System/360, System/370, ESA/390, and z/Architecture, all of them of type big-endian.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Numerous other orderings, generically called *middle-endian* or *mixed-endian*, are possible.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] The PDP-11 is primarily a 16-bit little-endian system.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] The instructions to convert between floating-point and integer values in the optional floating-point processor of the PDP-11/45, PDP-11/70, and in some later processors, stored 32-bit *double precision integer long* values with the 16-bit halves swapped from the expected little-endian order.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] The UNIX C compiler used the same format for 32-bit long integers.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] UNIX was one of the first systems to allow the same code to be compiled for platforms with different internal representations.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] One of the first programs converted was supposed to print out `Unix`, but on the Series/1 it printed `nUxi` instead.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Segment descriptors of IA-32 and compatible processors keep a 32-bit base address of the segment stored in little-endian order, but in four nonconsecutive bytes, at relative positions 2, 3, 4 and 7 of the descriptor start.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Hardware description languages (HDLs) used to express digital logic often support arbitrary endianness, with arbitrary granularity.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] For example, in SystemVerilog, a word can be defined as little-endian or big-endian.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] The recognition of endianness is important when reading a file or filesystem created on a computer with different endianness.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] An attempt to read such a file using Fortran on a system of the other endianness results in a run-time error, because the count fields are incorrect.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Unicode text can optionally start with a byte order mark (BOM) to signal the endianness of the file or stream.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] In UTF-32 for example, a big-endian file should start with `00 00 FE FF`; a little-endian should start with `FF FE 00 00`.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Application binary data formats, such as MATLAB *.mat* files, or the *.bil* data format, used in topography, are usually endianness-independent.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] This is achieved by storing the data always in one fixed endianness or carrying with the data a switch to indicate the endianness.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] An example of the former is the binary XLS file format that is portable between Windows and Mac systems and always little-endian, requiring the Mac application to swap the bytes on load and save when running on a big-endian Motorola 68K or PowerPC processor.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] TIFF image files are an example of the second strategy, whose header instructs the application about the endianness of their internal binary integers.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] If a file starts with the signature `MM` it means that integers are represented as big-endian, while `II` means little-endian.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Those signatures need a single 16-bit word each, and they are palindromes, so they are endianness independent.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] `I` stands for Intel and `M` stands for Motorola.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Intel CPUs are little-endian, while Motorola 680x0 CPUs are big-endian.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] This explicit signature allows a TIFF reader program to swap bytes if necessary when a given file was generated by a TIFF writer program running on a computer with a different endianness.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] ZFS, which combines a filesystem and a logical volume manager, is known to provide adaptive endianness and to work with both big-endian and little-endian systems.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Many IETF RFCs use the term *network order*, meaning the order of transmission for bytes *over the wire* in network protocols.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Among others, the historic RFC 1700 defines the network order for protocols in the Internet protocol suite to be big-endian.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] However, not all protocols use big-endian byte order as the network order.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] The Server Message Block (SMB) protocol uses little-endian byte order.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] In CANopen, multi-byte parameters are always sent least significant byte first (little-endian).
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] The same is true for Ethernet Powerlink.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] These functions may be a no-op on a big-endian system.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] While the high-level network protocols usually consider the byte (mostly meant as *octet*) as their atomic unit, the lowest layers of a network stack may deal with the ordering of bits within a byte.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Bit ordering is sometimes referred to as little-endian or big-endian.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Bit ordering does not need to be the same as byte ordering.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] For example, RS-232 transmits bits least significant first, I2C transmits bits most significant first, and SPI can be sent in either order.
[src:arm-riscv/endianness] Ethernet transmits individual bits least significant first, but bytes are sent big-endian.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] An **instruction set architecture** (**ISA**) is an abstract model that defines the programmable interface of the CPU of a computer, defining how software interacts with hardware.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] CPU) that interprets instructions described by an ISA is an implementation of that ISA.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Generally, the same ISA is used for a family of related CPU devices.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] In general, an ISA defines the instructions, data types, registers, and the programming interface for managing main memory such as addressing modes, virtual memory, and memory consistency mechanisms.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] The ISA also includes the input/output model of the programmable interface.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] An ISA specifies the behavior implied by machine code running on an implementation of that ISA in a fashion that does not depend on the characteristics of that implementation, providing binary compatibility between implementations.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] It also enables the evolution of the microarchitectures of the implementations of that ISA, so that a newer, higher-performance implementation of an ISA can run software that runs on previous generations of implementations.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] If an operating system maintains a standard and compatible application binary interface (ABI) for a particular ISA, machine code will run on future implementations of that ISA and operating system.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] However, if an ISA supports running multiple operating systems, it does not guarantee that machine code for one operating system will run on another operating system, unless the first operating system supports running machine code built for the other operating system.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] An ISA can be extended by adding instructions or other capabilities, or adding support for larger addresses and data values; an implementation of the extended ISA will still be able to execute machine code for versions of the ISA without those extensions.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Machine code using those extensions will only run on implementations that support those extensions.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] The binary compatibility that they provide makes ISAs one of the most fundamental abstractions in computing.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] An instruction set architecture is distinguished from a microarchitecture, which is the set of processor design techniques used, in a particular processor, to implement the instruction set.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Processors with different microarchitectures can share a common instruction set.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] For example, the Intel Pentium and the AMD Athlon implement nearly identical versions of the x86 instruction set, but they have radically different internal designs.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] The concept of an *architecture*, distinct from the design of a specific machine, was developed by Fred Brooks at IBM during the design phase of System/360.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Some virtual machines that support bytecode as their ISA such as Smalltalk, the Java virtual machine, and Microsoft's Common Language Runtime, implement this by translating the bytecode for commonly used code paths into native machine code.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] In addition, these virtual machines execute less frequently used code paths by interpretation (see: Just-in-time compilation).
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Transmeta implemented the x86 instruction set atop very long instruction word (VLIW) processors in this fashion.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] An ISA may be classified in a number of different ways.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] A common classification is by architectural *complexity*.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] A complex instruction set computer (CISC) has many specialized instructions, some of which may only be rarely used in practical programs.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Other types include VLIW architectures, and the closely related *long instruction word* (LIW) and *explicitly parallel instruction computing* (EPIC) architectures.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] These architectures seek to exploit instruction-level parallelism with less hardware than RISC and CISC by making the compiler responsible for instruction issue and scheduling.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Architectures with even less complexity have been studied, such as the minimal instruction set computer (MISC) and one-instruction set computer (OISC).
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] These are theoretically important types, but have not been commercialized.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Machine language is built up from discrete *statements* or *instructions*.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] More complex operations are built up by combining these simple instructions, which are executed sequentially, or as otherwise directed by control flow instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Processors may include elaborate instructions in their instruction set.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] A single elaborate instruction does something that may require many instructions or a subroutine on other computers.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Such instructions are typified by instructions that take multiple steps, control multiple functional units, or otherwise appear on a larger scale than the bulk of simple instructions implemented by the given processor.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Elaborate instructions are more common in CISC instruction sets than in RISC instruction sets, but RISC instruction sets may include them as well.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] RISC instruction sets generally do not include ALU operations with memory operands, or instructions to move large blocks of memory, but most RISC instruction sets include SIMD or vector instructions that perform the same arithmetic operation on multiple pieces of data at the same time.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] SIMD instructions have the ability of manipulating large vectors and matrices in minimal time.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] SIMD instructions allow easy parallelization of algorithms commonly involved in sound, image, and video processing.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Various SIMD implementations have been brought to market under trade names such as MMX, 3DNow!, and AltiVec.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] On traditional architectures, an instruction includes an opcode that specifies the operation to perform, such as *add contents of memory to register*—and zero or more operand specifiers, which may specify registers, memory locations, or literal data.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] The operand specifiers may have addressing modes determining their meaning or may be in fixed fields.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] In very long instruction word (VLIW) architectures, which include many microcode architectures, multiple simultaneous opcodes and operands are specified in a single instruction.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Some exotic instruction sets do not have an opcode field, such as transport triggered architectures (TTA), only operand(s).
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Most stack machines have "0-operand" instruction sets in which arithmetic and logical operations lack any operand specifier fields; only instructions that push operands onto the evaluation stack or that pop operands from the stack into variables have operand specifiers.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] The instruction set carries out most ALU actions with postfix (reverse Polish notation) operations that work only on the expression stack, not on data registers or arbitrary main memory cells.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] This can be very convenient for compiling high-level languages, because most arithmetic expressions can be easily translated into postfix notation.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Conditional instructions often have a predicate field—a few bits that encode the specific condition to cause an operation to be performed rather than not performed.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] For example, a conditional branch instruction will transfer control if the condition is true, so that execution proceeds to a different part of the program, and not transfer control if the condition is false, so that execution continues sequentially.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Some instruction sets also have conditional moves, so that the move will be executed, and the data stored in the target location, if the condition is true, and not executed, and the target location not modified, if the condition is false.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Similarly, IBM z/Architecture has a conditional store instruction.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] A few instruction sets include a predicate field in every instruction.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Having predicates on instructions is called predication, and can *include* conditional-branches, such as `bf` on the SuperH.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Many architectures have conditional branch instructions designed for controlling loops.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Typically, they update and test a register.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Instruction sets may be categorized by the maximum number of operands *explicitly* specified in instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Due to the large number of bits needed to encode the three registers of a 3-operand instruction, RISC architectures that have 16-bit instructions are invariably 2-operand designs, such as the Atmel AVR, TI MSP430, and some versions of ARM Thumb.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] RISC architectures that have 32-bit instructions are usually 3-operand designs, such as the ARM, AVR32, MIPS, Power ISA, and SPARC architectures.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] However even 3-operand RISC architectures will, at considerable cost, have Fused multiply-and-add 4-operand instructions out of necessity, due to the increased accuracy provided.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Modern examples include Power ISA and RISC-V.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Each instruction specifies some number of operands (registers, memory locations, or immediate values) *explicitly*.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Some instructions give one or both operands implicitly, such as by being stored on top of the stack or in an implicit register.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] If some of the operands are given implicitly, fewer operands need be specified in the instruction.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] When a "destination operand" explicitly specifies the destination, an additional operand must be supplied.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Consequently, the number of operands encoded in an instruction may differ from the mathematically necessary number of arguments for a logical or arithmetic operation (the arity).
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Operands are either encoded in the "opcode" representation of the instruction, or else are given as values or addresses following the opcode.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] While embedded instruction sets such as Thumb suffer from extremely high register pressure because they have small register sets, general-purpose RISC ISAs like MIPS and Alpha enjoy low register pressure.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] CISC ISAs like x86-64 offer low register pressure despite having smaller register sets.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] This is due to the many addressing modes and optimizations (such as sub-register addressing, memory operands in ALU instructions, absolute addressing, PC-relative addressing, and register-to-register spills) that CISC ISAs offer.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] The size or length of an instruction varies widely, from as little as four bits in some microcontrollers to many hundreds of bits in some VLIW systems.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Processors used in personal computers, mainframes, and supercomputers have minimum instruction sizes between 8 and 64 bits.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] The longest possible instruction on x86 is 15 bytes (120 bits).
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Within an instruction set, different instructions may have different lengths.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] In some architectures, notably most reduced instruction set computers (RISC), instructions are a fixed length, typically corresponding with that architecture's word size.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] In other architectures, instructions have variable length, typically integral multiples of a byte or a halfword.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Some, such as the ARM with *Thumb-extension* have *mixed* variable encoding, that is two fixed, usually 32-bit and 16-bit encodings, where instructions cannot be mixed freely but must be switched between on a branch (or exception boundary in ARMv8).
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Fixed-length instructions are less complicated to handle than variable-length instructions for several reasons (not having to check whether an instruction straddles a cache line or virtual memory page boundary, for instance), and are therefore somewhat easier to optimize for speed.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] In early 1960s computers, main memory was expensive and very limited, even on mainframes.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Minimizing the size of a program to make sure it would fit in the limited memory was often central.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Thus the size of the instructions needed to perform a particular task, the *code density*, was an important characteristic of any instruction set.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] It remained important on the initially-tiny memories of minicomputers and then microprocessors.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Density remains important today, for smartphone applications, applications downloaded into browsers over slow Internet connections, and in ROMs for embedded applications.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] A more general advantage of increased density is improved effectiveness of caches and instruction prefetch.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Computers with high code density often have complex instructions for procedure entry, parameterized returns, loops, etc.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] (therefore retroactively named *Complex Instruction Set Computers*, CISC).
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] However, more typical, or frequent, "CISC" instructions merely combine a basic ALU operation, such as "add", with the access of one or more operands in memory (using addressing modes such as direct, indirect, indexed, etc.).
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Certain architectures may allow two or three operands (including the result) directly in memory or may be able to perform functions such as automatic pointer increment, etc.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Software-implemented instruction sets may have even more complex and powerful instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Certain embedded RISC ISAs like Thumb and AVR32 typically exhibit very high density owing to a technique called code compression.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] This technique packs two 16-bit instructions into one 32-bit word, which is then unpacked at the decode stage and executed as two instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Minimal instruction set computers (MISC) are commonly a form of stack machine, where there are few separate instructions (8–32), so that multiple instructions can be fit into a single machine word.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] These types of cores often take little silicon to implement, so they can be easily realized in an FPGA (field-programmable gate array) or in a multi-core form.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] The code density of MISC is similar to the code density of RISC; the increased instruction density is offset by requiring more of the primitive instructions to do a task.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] There has been research into executable compression as a mechanism for improving code density.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] The mathematics of Kolmogorov complexity describes the challenges and limits of this.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] In practice, code density is also dependent on the compiler.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Most optimizing compilers have options that control whether to optimize code generation for execution speed or for code density.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] For instance GCC has the option `-Os` to optimize for small machine code size, and `-O3` to optimize for execution speed at the cost of larger machine code.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] The instructions constituting a program are rarely specified using their internal, numeric form (machine code); they may be specified by programmers using an assembly language or, more commonly, may be generated from high-level programming languages by compilers.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] The design of instruction sets is a complex issue.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] There were two stages in history for the microprocessor.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] The first was the CISC (complex instruction set computer), which had many different instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] In the 1970s, however, places like IBM did research and found that many instructions in the set could be eliminated.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] The result was the RISC (reduced instruction set computer), an architecture that uses a smaller set of instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] A simpler instruction set may offer the potential for higher speeds, reduced processor size, and reduced power consumption.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] However, a more complex set may optimize common operations, improve memory and cache efficiency, or simplify programming.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Some instruction set designers reserve one or more opcodes for some kind of system call or software interrupt.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] For example, MOS Technology 6502 uses 00H, Zilog Z80 uses the eight codes C7,CF,D7,DF,E7,EF,F7,FFH while Motorola 68000 use codes in the range 4E40H-4E4FH.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Fast virtual machines are much easier to implement if an instruction set meets the Popek and Goldberg virtualization requirements.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] The NOP slide used in immunity-aware programming is much easier to implement if the "unprogrammed" state of the memory is interpreted as a NOP.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] On systems with multiple processors, non-blocking synchronization algorithms are much easier to implement if the instruction set includes support for something such as "fetch-and-add", "load-link/store-conditional" (LL/SC), or "atomic compare-and-swap".
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] A given instruction set can be implemented in a variety of ways.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] All ways of implementing a particular instruction set provide the same programming model, and all implementations of that instruction set are able to run the same executables.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] The various ways of implementing an instruction set give different tradeoffs between cost, performance, power consumption, size, etc.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] When designing the microarchitecture of a processor, engineers use blocks of "hard-wired" electronic circuitry (often designed separately) such as adders, multiplexers, counters, registers, ALUs, etc.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Some kind of register transfer language is then often used to describe the decoding and sequencing of each instruction of an ISA using this physical microarchitecture.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Other designs employ microcode routines or tables (or both) to do this, using ROMs or writable RAMs (writable control store), PLAs, or both.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Some microcoded CPU designs with a writable control store use it to allow the instruction set to be changed (for example, the Rekursiv processor and the Imsys Cjip).
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] CPUs designed for reconfigurable computing may use field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs).
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] An ISA can also be emulated in software by an interpreter.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Naturally, due to the interpretation overhead, this is slower than directly running programs on the emulated hardware, unless the hardware running the emulator is an order of magnitude faster.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Today, it is common practice for vendors of new ISAs or microarchitectures to make software emulators available to software developers before the hardware implementation is ready.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] Often the details of the implementation have a strong influence on the particular instructions selected for the instruction set.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] For example, many implementations of the instruction pipeline only allow a single memory load or memory store per instruction, leading to a load–store architecture (RISC).
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] For another example, some early ways of implementing the instruction pipeline led to a delay slot.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] The demands of high-speed digital signal processing have pushed in the opposite direction—forcing instructions to be implemented in a particular way.
[src:arm-riscv/instruction-set-architecture] For example, to perform digital filters fast enough, the MAC instruction in a typical digital signal processor (DSP) must use a kind of Harvard architecture that can fetch an instruction and two data words simultaneously, and it requires a single-cycle multiply–accumulate multiplier.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In electronics and computer science, a **reduced instruction set computer** (**RISC**, pronounced "risk") is a computer architecture designed to simplify the individual instructions given to the computer to accomplish tasks.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Compared to the instructions given to a complex instruction set computer (CISC), a RISC computer might require more machine code in order to accomplish a task because the individual instructions perform simpler operations.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The goal is to offset the need to process more instructions by increasing the speed of each instruction, in particular by implementing an instruction pipeline, which may be simpler to achieve given simpler instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The key operational concept of the RISC computer is that each instruction performs only one function (e.g., copy a value from memory to a register).
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The design of the CPU allows RISC computers few and simple addressing modes and predictable instruction times that simplify design of the system as a whole.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The conceptual developments of the RISC computer architecture began with the IBM 801 project in the late 1970s, but these were not immediately put into use.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Designers in California picked up the 801 concepts in two seminal projects, Stanford MIPS and Berkeley RISC.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] These were commercialized in the 1980s as the MIPS and SPARC systems.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] IBM eventually produced RISC designs based on further work on the 801 concept, the IBM POWER architecture, PowerPC, and Power ISA.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] RISC processors are used in supercomputers, such as the Fugaku.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The varieties of RISC processor design include the ARC processor, the DEC Alpha, the AMD Am29000, the ARM architecture, the Atmel AVR, Blackfin, Intel i860, Intel i960, LoongArch, Motorola 88000, the MIPS architecture, PA-RISC, Power ISA, RISC-V, SuperH, and SPARC.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] A number of systems, going back to the 1960s, have been credited as the first RISC architecture, partly based on their use of the load–store approach.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The term RISC was coined by David Patterson of the Berkeley RISC project, although somewhat similar concepts had appeared before.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The CDC 6600 designed by Seymour Cray in 1964 used a load–store architecture with only two addressing modes (register+register, and register+immediate constant) and 74 operation codes, with the basic clock cycle being 10 times faster than the memory access time.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Partly due to the optimized load–store architecture of the CDC 6600, Jack Dongarra says that it can be considered a forerunner of modern RISC systems, although a number of other technical barriers needed to be overcome for the development of a modern RISC system.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Flynn views the first RISC system as the IBM 801 design, begun in 1975 by John Cocke and completed in 1980.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The 801 developed out of an effort to build a 24-bit high-speed processor to use as the basis for a digital telephone switch.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] To reach their goal of switching 1 million calls per hour (300 per second) they calculated that the CPU required performance on the order of 12 million instructions per second (MIPS), compared to their fastest mainframe machine of the time, the 370/168, which performed at 3.5 MIPS.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The design was based on a study of IBM's extensive collection of statistics gathered from its customers.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This demonstrated that code in high-performance settings made extensive use of processor registers, and that they often ran out of them.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This suggested that additional registers would improve performance.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Additionally, they noticed that compilers generally ignored the vast majority of the available instructions, especially orthogonal addressing modes.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Instead, they selected the fastest version of any given instruction and then constructed small routines using it.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This suggested that the majority of instructions could be removed without affecting the resulting code.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] These two conclusions worked in concert; removing instructions would allow the instruction opcodes to be shorter, freeing up bits in the instruction word which could then be used to select among a larger set of registers.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The telephone switch program was canceled in 1975, but by then the team had demonstrated that the same design would offer significant performance gains running just about any code.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In simulations, they showed that a compiler tuned to use registers instead of operating directly on memory would run code about three times as fast as traditional designs.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Somewhat surprisingly, the same code would run about 50% faster even on existing machines due to the improved register use.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In practice, their experimental PL/8 compiler, a slightly cut-down version of PL/I, consistently produced code that ran much faster on their existing mainframes.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] A 32-bit version of the 801 was eventually produced in a single-chip form as the IBM ROMP in 1981, which stood for 'Research OPD [Office Products Division] Micro Processor'.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This CPU was designed for "mini" tasks, and found use in peripheral interfaces and channel controllers on later IBM computers.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] It was also used as the CPU in the IBM RT PC in 1986, which turned out to be a commercial failure.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Although the 801 did not see widespread use in its original form, it inspired many research projects, including ones at IBM that would eventually lead to the IBM POWER architecture.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] By the late 1970s, the 801 had become well-known in the industry.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This coincided with new fabrication techniques that were allowing more complex chips to come to market.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] These newer designs generally used their newfound complexity to expand the instruction set to make it more orthogonal.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Most, like the 68k, used microcode to do this, reading instructions and re-implementing them as a sequence of simpler internal instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In the 68k, a full 1⁄3 of the transistors were used for this microcoding.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In 1979, David Patterson was sent on a sabbatical from the University of California, Berkeley to help DEC's west-coast team improve the VAX microcode.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Patterson was struck by the complexity of the coding process and concluded it was untenable.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] He first wrote a paper on ways to improve microcoding, but later changed his mind and decided microcode itself was the problem.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] With funding from the DARPA VLSI Program, Patterson started the Berkeley RISC effort.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The program, practically unknown today, led to a huge number of advances in chip design, fabrication, and even computer graphics.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Considering a variety of programs from their BSD Unix variant, the Berkeley team found, as had IBM, that most programs made no use of the large variety of instructions in the 68k.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Patterson's early work pointed out an important problem with the traditional "more is better" approach; even those instructions that were critical to overall performance were being delayed by their trip through the microcode.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] If the microcode was removed, the programs would run faster.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] And since the microcode ultimately took a complex instruction and broke it into steps, there was no reason the compiler could not do this instead.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] These studies suggested that, even with no other changes, one could make a chip with 1⁄3 fewer transistors that would run faster.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] It was also discovered that, on microcoded implementations of certain architectures, complex operations tended to be *slower* than a sequence of simpler operations doing the same thing.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] One infamous example was the VAX's `INDEX` instruction.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The Berkeley work also turned up a number of additional points.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Among these was the fact that programs spent a significant amount of time performing subroutine calls and returns, and it seemed there was the potential to improve overall performance by speeding up these calls.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This led the Berkeley design to select a method known as register windows, which can significantly improve subroutine performance, although at the cost of some complexity.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] They also noticed that the majority of mathematical instructions were simple assignments; only 1⁄3 of them actually performed an operation like addition or subtraction.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] But when those operations did occur, they tended to be slow.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This led to far more emphasis on the underlying arithmetic data unit, as opposed to previous designs where the majority of the chip was dedicated to control and microcode.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The resulting Berkeley RISC was based on gaining performance through the use of pipelining and aggressive use of register windowing.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In a traditional CPU, one has a small number of registers, and a program can use any register at any time.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In a CPU with register windows, there are a huge number of registers, e.g., 128, but programs can only use a small number of them, e.g., eight, at any one time.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] A program that limits itself to eight registers per procedure can make very fast procedure calls: The call simply moves the window "down" by eight, to the set of eight registers used by that procedure, and the return moves the window back.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The Berkeley RISC project delivered the RISC-I processor in 1982.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Consisting of only 44,420 transistors (compared with averages of about 100,000 in newer CISC designs of the era), RISC-I had only 32 instructions, and yet completely outperformed any other single-chip design, with estimated performance being higher than the VAX.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] They followed this up with the 40,760-transistor, 39-instruction RISC-II in 1983, which ran over three times as fast as RISC-I.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] As the RISC project began to become known in Silicon Valley, a similar project began at Stanford University in 1981.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This MIPS project grew out of a graduate course by John L.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Hennessy, produced a functioning system in 1983, and could run simple programs by 1984.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The MIPS approach emphasized an aggressive clock cycle and the use of the pipeline, making sure it could be run as "full" as possible.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The MIPS system was followed by the MIPS-X, and in 1984 Hennessy and his colleagues formed MIPS Computer Systems to produce the design commercially.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The venture resulted in a new architecture that was also called MIPS and the R2000 microprocessor in 1985.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Competition between RISC and conventional CISC approaches was also the subject of theoretical analysis in the early 1980s, leading, for example, to the iron law of processor performance.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Since 2010, a new open standard instruction set architecture (ISA), Berkeley RISC-V, has been under development at the University of California, Berkeley, for research purposes and as a free alternative to proprietary ISAs.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] As of 2014, version 2 of the user space ISA is fixed.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The ISA is designed to be extensible from a barebones core sufficient for a small embedded processor to supercomputer and cloud computing use with standard and chip designer–defined extensions and coprocessors.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] It has been tested in silicon design with the ROCKET SoC, which is also available as an open-source processor generator in the CHISEL language.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In the early 1980s, significant uncertainties surrounded the RISC concept.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] One concern involved the use of memory; a single instruction from a traditional processor like the Motorola 68k may be written out as perhaps a half dozen of the simpler RISC instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In theory, this could slow the system down as it spends more time fetching instructions from memory.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] But by the mid-1980s, the concepts had matured enough to be seen as commercially viable.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In the minicomputer market, companies including Celerity Computing, Pyramid Technology, and Ridge Computers began offering systems designed according to RISC or RISC-like principles in the early 1980s.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Few of these designs began by using RISC microprocessors.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Commercial RISC designs began to emerge in the mid-1980s.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The IBM RT PC was introduced in January 1986, and the Acorn ARM1 was introduced as part of an evaluation system in July 1986, following on from initial fabrication in April 1985.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The MIPS R2000 was introduced in May 1986, followed shortly thereafter by Hewlett-Packard's PA-RISC in some of their computers.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In the meantime, the Berkeley effort had become so well known that it eventually became the name for the entire concept.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In 1987, Sun Microsystems began shipping systems with the SPARC processor, directly based on the Berkeley RISC-II system.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The US government Committee on Innovations in Computing and Communications credits the acceptance of the viability of the RISC concept to the success of the SPARC system.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] A benefit of RISC to the industry was much lower prices than the sole sourced Intel 80386; by 1989 many RISC CPUs were available, and competition lowered their price to $10 per MIPS in large quantities.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The performance of IBM's RISC CPU—only available in the RT PC—was less competitive than others, but the success of SPARC renewed interest within IBM, which released new RISC systems by 1990 and by 1995 RISC processors were the foundation of a $15 billion server industry.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Patterson was a consultant for Intel during the 1980s.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Despite dominating the microprocessor market with the CISC 80386 and its successors, the consensus that RISC was the future of the industry influenced that company's engineers, who worked to improve the performance of their processors to match RISC.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] IBM chose a similar approach of improving CISC as much as possible with IBM mainframes, while introducing new RISC-based computers that competed directly with its existing CISC midrange systems.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Sun's move to SPARC was based on its decision to, instead of relying on improvements to CISC, transition to RISC as fast as possible.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The DEC engineers who designed DECstation with MIPS R2000 and not their company's own VAX did so because, they wrote, the former offered "at least a two-to-one performance advantage" for the cost.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] By the later 1980s, new RISC designs were easily outperforming all CISC designs by a wide margin.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] By 1992 Sun, DEC, HP, and IBM were the leading commercial RISC companies.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Other vendors began their own RISC efforts.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Among the available architectures were the DEC Alpha, AMD Am29000, Intel i860 and i960, Motorola 88000, IBM POWER, and, slightly later, the IBM/Apple/Motorola PowerPC.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Many of these have since disappeared due to them often offering no competitive advantage over others of the same era.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Those that remain are often used only in niche markets or as parts of other systems; of the designs from these traditional vendors, only SPARC and the PowerPC-derived Power ISA have any significant remaining market.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] With the rise in mobile, automotive, streaming, smart device computing, ARM became the most widely used ISA, the company estimating that almost half of all CPUs shipped in history have been ARM.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] A common misunderstanding of the phrase "reduced instruction set computer" is that instructions are simply eliminated, resulting in a smaller set of instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In fact, over the years, RISC instruction sets have grown in size, and today many of them have a larger set of instructions than many CISC CPUs.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Some RISC processors such as the PowerPC have instruction sets as large as the CISC IBM System/370, for example; conversely, the DEC PDP-8—clearly a CISC CPU because many of its instructions involve multiple memory accesses—has only 8 basic instructions and a few extended instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The term *load–store architecture* is sometimes preferred.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Another way of looking at the RISC/CISC debate is to consider what is exposed to the compiler.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In a CISC processor, the hardware may internally use registers and flag bits in order to implement a single complex instruction such as `STRING MOVE`, but hide those details from the compiler.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The internal operations of a RISC processor are "exposed to the compiler", leading to the backronym 'Relegate Interesting Stuff to the Compiler'.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Most RISC architectures have fixed-length instructions and a simple encoding, which simplifies fetch, decode, and issue logic considerably.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This is among the main goals of the RISC approach.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Some of this is possible only due to the contemporary move to 32-bit formats.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] For instance, in a typical program, over 30% of all the numeric constants are either 0 or 1, 95% will fit in one byte, and 99% in a 16-bit value.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] When computers were based on 8- or 16-bit words, it would be difficult to have an immediate combined with the opcode in a single memory word, although certain instructions like increment and decrement did this implicitly by using a different opcode.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In contrast, a 32-bit machine has ample room to encode an immediate value, and doing so avoids the need to do a second memory read to pick up the value.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This is why many RISC processors allow a 12- or 13-bit constant to be encoded directly into the instruction word.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Assuming a 13-bit constant area, as is the case in the MIPS and RISC designs, another 19 bits are available for the instruction encoding.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This leaves ample room to indicate both the opcode and one or two registers.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Register-to-register operations, mostly math and logic, require enough bits to encode the two or three registers being used.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Most processors use the three-operand format `A = B + C`, in which case three register numbers are needed.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] If the processor has 32 registers, each one requires a 5-bit number for 15 bits total.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] If one of these registers is replaced by an immediate, there is still room to encode the two remaining registers and the opcode.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Common instructions found in multi-word systems, like `INC` and `DEC`, which reduce the number of words that have to be read before performing the instruction, are unnecessary in RISC as they can be accomplished with a single register and the immediate value 1.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The original RISC-I format remains a canonical example of the concept.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] It uses 7 bits for the opcode and a 1-bit flag for conditional codes, the following 5 bits for the destination register, and the next five for the first operand.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This leaves 14 bits, the first of which indicates whether the following 13 contain an immediate value or uses only five of them to indicate a register for the second operand.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] A more complex example is the MIPS encoding, which uses only 6 bits for the opcode, followed by two 5-bit registers.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The remaining 16 bits could be used in two ways: one as a 16-bit immediate value, or as a 5-bit shift value (used only in shift operations, otherwise zero) and the remaining 6 bits as an extension on the opcode.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In the case of register-to-register arithmetic operations, the opcode was 0 and the last 6 bits contained the actual code; those that used an immediate value used the normal opcode field at the front.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] One drawback of 32-bit instructions is reduced code density, which is a more adverse characteristic in embedded computing than it is in the workstation and server markets that RISC architectures were originally designed to serve.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] To address this problem, several architectures, such as SuperH (1992), ARM thumb (1994), MIPS16e (2004), Power Variable Length Encoding ISA (2006), RISC-V, and the Adapteva Epiphany, have an optional short, feature-reduced compressed instruction set.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Generally, these instructions expose a smaller number of registers and fewer bits for immediate values, and often use a two-operand format to eliminate one register number from instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] A two-operand format in a system with 16 registers requires 8 bits for register numbers, leaving another 8 for an opcode or other uses.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The SH5 also follows this pattern, albeit having evolved in the opposite direction, having added longer 32-bit instructions to an original 16-bit encoding.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The most characteristic aspect of RISC is executing at least one instruction per cycle.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Single-cycle operation is described as "the rapid execution of simple functions that dominate a computer's instruction stream", thus seeking to deliver an average throughput approaching one instruction per cycle for any single instruction stream.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Many early RISC designs also shared the characteristic of having a branch delay slot, an instruction space immediately following a jump or branch.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The instruction in this space is executed, whether or not the branch is taken (in other words, the effect of the branch is delayed).
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This instruction keeps the ALU of the CPU busy for the extra time normally needed to perform a branch.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Nowadays, the branch delay slot is considered an unfortunate side effect of a particular strategy for implementing some RISC designs, and modern RISC designs generally do away with it (such as PowerPC and more recent versions of SPARC and MIPS).
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] It was argued that such functions would be better performed by sequences of simpler instructions if this could yield implementations small enough to leave room for many registers, reducing the number of slow memory accesses.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] In these simple designs, most instructions are of uniform length and similar structure, arithmetic operations are restricted to CPU registers and only separate *load* and *store* instructions access memory.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] These properties enable a better balancing of pipeline stages than before, making RISC pipelines significantly more efficient and allowing higher clock frequencies.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Yet another impetus of both RISC and other designs came from practical measurements on real-world programs.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Andrew Tanenbaum summed up many of these, demonstrating that processors often had oversized immediates.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] For instance, he showed that 98% of all the constants in a program would fit in 13 bits, yet many CPU designs dedicated 16 or 32 bits to store them.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This suggests that, to reduce the number of memory accesses, a fixed-length machine could store constants in unused bits of the instruction word itself, so that they would be immediately ready when the CPU needs them (much like immediate addressing in a conventional design).
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This required small opcodes in order to leave room for a reasonably sized constant in a 32-bit instruction word.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Since many real-world programs spend most of their time executing simple operations, some researchers decided to focus on making those operations as fast as possible.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The clock rate of a CPU is limited by the time it takes to execute the slowest *sub-operation* of any instruction; decreasing that cycle-time often accelerates the execution of other instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The focus on "reduced instructions" led to the resulting machine being called a "reduced instruction set computer" (RISC).
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] The goal was to make instructions so simple that they could *easily* be pipelined, in order to achieve a *single clock* throughput at *high frequencies*.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This contrasted with CISC designs whose "crucial arithmetic operations and register transfers" were considered difficult to pipeline.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Later, it was noted that one of the most significant characteristics of RISC processors was that external memory was only accessible by a *load* or *store* instruction.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] All other instructions were limited to internal registers.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This simplified many aspects of processor design: allowing instructions to be fixed-length, simplifying pipelines, and isolating the logic for dealing with the delay in completing a memory access (cache miss, etc.) to only two instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] This led to RISC designs being referred to as *load–store* architectures.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Some CPUs have been specifically designed to have a very small set of instructions—but these designs are very different from classic RISC designs, so they have been given other names such as minimal instruction set computer (MISC) or transport triggered architecture (TTA).
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] RISC architectures have traditionally had few successes in the desktop PC and commodity server markets, where the x86-based platforms remain the dominant processor architecture.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] However, this may change, as ARM-based processors are being developed for higher-performance systems.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Manufacturers including Cavium, AMD, and Qualcomm have released server processors based on the ARM architecture.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] ARM further partnered with Cray in 2017 to produce an ARM-based supercomputer.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] On the desktop, Microsoft announced that it planned to support the PC version of Windows 10 on Qualcomm Snapdragon-based devices in 2017 as part of its partnership with Qualcomm.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] These devices will support Windows applications compiled for 32-bit x86 via an x86 processor emulator that translates 32-bit x86 code to ARM64 code.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Apple announced they will transition their Mac desktop and laptop computers from Intel processors to internally developed ARM64-based SoCs called Apple silicon; the first such computers, using the Apple M1 processor, were released in November 2020.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Macs with Apple silicon can run x86-64 binaries with Rosetta 2, an x86-64 to ARM64 translator.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Outside of the desktop arena, however, the ARM RISC architecture is in widespread use in smartphones, tablets and many forms of embedded devices.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] While early RISC designs differed significantly from contemporary CISC designs, by 2000 the highest-performing CPUs in the RISC line were almost indistinguishable from the highest-performing CPUs in the CISC line.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] RISC architectures are now used across a range of platforms, from smartphones and tablet computers to some of the world's fastest supercomputers such as Fugaku, the fastest on the TOP500 list as of November 2020, and Summit, Sierra, and Sunway TaihuLight, the next three on that list.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] By the beginning of the 21st century, the majority of low-end and mobile systems relied on RISC architectures.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] RISC architectures have become popular in open source processors and soft microprocessors since they are relatively simple to implement, which makes them suitable for FPGA implementations and prototyping, for instance.
[src:arm-riscv/reduced-instruction-set-computer] Wilson were awarded the Charles Stark Draper Prize by the United States National Academy of Engineering for their contributions to the invention, development, and implementation of reduced instruction set computer (RISC) chips.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] RISC-V was developed in 2010 at the University of California, Berkeley as the fifth generation of RISC processors created at the university since 1981.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] In 2015, development and maintenance of the standard was transferred to **RISC-V International**, a non-profit organization based in Switzerland with more than 4,500 members as of 2025.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] RISC-V is a popular architecture for microcontrollers and embedded systems, with development of higher-performance implementations targeting mobile, desktop, and server markets ongoing.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] Before then, there was some knowledge (see John Cocke) that simpler computers can be effective, but the design principles were not widely described.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] Simple, effective computers have always been of academic interest, and resulted in the RISC instruction set DLX for the first edition of *Computer Architecture: A Quantitative Approach* in 1990 of which David Patterson was a co-author, and he later participated in the RISC-V origination.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] DLX was intended for educational use; academics and hobbyists implemented it using field-programmable gate arrays (FPGA), but it was never truly intended for commercial deployment.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] Krste Asanović at the University of California, Berkeley, had a research requirement for an open-source CPU core, and in 2010, he decided to develop and publish his own, in a "short, three-month project over the summer" with several of his graduate students.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] Several established open-source alternatives were available, but Asanović chose not to use them.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] ARM and SuperH CPUs (versions 2 and earlier) had public-domain instruction sets with VHDL implementation files, while complete OpenRISC, OpenPOWER, and OpenSPARC / LEON cores were also available either as VHDL files or from various vendors.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] All of these existing options were supported by the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC), a popular free-software compiler, and had Linux kernel support.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] The plan was to aid both academic and industrial users.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] At this stage, students provided initial software, simulations, and CPU designs.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] The RISC-V authors and their institution originally sourced the ISA documents and several CPU designs under BSD licenses, which allow derivative works—such as RISC-V chip designs—to be either open and free, or closed and proprietary.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] The ISA specification itself (i.e., the encoding of the instruction set) was published in 2011 as open source, with all rights reserved.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] The actual technical report (an expression of the specification) was later placed under the license Creative Commons - Attribution 4.0 to permit enhancement by external contributors through the RISC-V Foundation, and later RISC-V International.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] A full history of RISC-V has been published on the RISC-V International website.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] Commercial users require an ISA to be stable before they can use it in a product that may last many years.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] To address this issue, the RISC-V Foundation was formed in 2015 to own, maintain, and publish intellectual property related to RISC-V's definition.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] The original authors and owners have surrendered their rights to the foundation.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] The foundation was led by CEO Calista Redmond, who took on the role in 2019 after leading open infrastructure projects at IBM.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] In November 2019, the RISC-V Foundation announced that it would relocate to Switzerland, citing concerns over U.S. trade regulations.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] As of March 2020, the organization was named RISC-V International, a Swiss nonprofit business association.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] As of 2019, RISC-V International freely publishes the documents defining RISC-V and permits unrestricted use of the ISA for design of software and hardware.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] However, only members of RISC-V International can vote to approve changes, and only member organizations use the trademarked compatibility logo.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] The Linux Foundation Europe started the RISC-V Software Ecosystem (RISE) initiative on May 31, 2023.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] The goal of RISE is to increase the availability of software for high-performance and power-efficient RISC-V processors running high-level operating systems for a range of market segments by bringing together a large number of hardware and software vendors.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] Red Hat, Samsung, Qualcomm, Nvidia, MediaTek, Intel, and Google are among the initial members.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] CPU design requires design expertise in several specialties: electronic digital logic, compilers, and operating systems.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] To cover the costs of such a team, commercial vendors of processor intellectual property (IP), such as Arm Ltd. and MIPS Technologies, charge royalties for the use of their designs and patents.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] They also often require non-disclosure agreements before releasing documents that describe their designs' detailed advantages.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] In many cases, they never describe the reasons for their design choices.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] RISC-V was begun with a goal to make a practical ISA that was open-sourced, usable academically, and deployable in any hardware or software design without royalties.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] Also, justifying rationales for each design decision of the project are explained, at least in broad terms.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] The RISC-V authors are academics who have substantial experience in computer design, and the RISC-V ISA is a direct development from a series of academic computer-design projects, especially Berkeley RISC.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] RISC-V was originated in part to aid all such projects.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] To build a large, continuing community of users and thereby accumulate designs and software, the RISC-V ISA designers intentionally support a wide variety of practical use cases: compact, performance, and low-power real-world implementations without over-architecting for a given microarchitecture.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] The requirements of a large base of contributors is part of the reason why RISC-V was engineered to address many possible uses.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] The designers' primary assertion is that the instruction set is the key interface in a computer as it is situated at the interface between the hardware and the software.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] If a good instruction set were open and available for use by all, then it can dramatically reduce the cost of software by enabling far more reuse.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] It should also trigger increased competition among hardware providers, who can then devote more resources toward design and less for software support.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] The designers maintain that new principles are becoming rare in instruction set design, as the most successful designs of the last forty years have grown increasingly similar.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] Of those that failed, most did so because their sponsoring companies were financially unsuccessful, not because the instruction sets were technically poor.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] Thus, a well-designed open instruction set designed using well-established principles should attract long-term support by many vendors.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] The simplicity of the integer subset permits basic student exercises, and is a simple enough ISA to enable software to control research machines.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] The variable-length ISA provides room for instruction set extensions for both student exercises and research, and the separated privileged instruction set permits research in operating system support without redesigning compilers.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] RISC-V's open intellectual property paradigm allows derivative designs to be published, reused, and modified.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] RISC-V has a modular design, consisting of alternative base parts, with added optional extensions.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] The ISA base and its extensions are developed in a collective effort between industry, the research community and educational institutions.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] The base specifies instructions (and their encoding), control flow, registers (and their sizes), memory and addressing, logic (i.e., integer) manipulation, and ancillaries.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] The base alone can implement a simplified general-purpose computer, with full software support, including a general-purpose compiler.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] The standard extensions are specified to work with all of the standard bases, and with each other without conflict.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] Many RISC-V computers might implement the compressed instructions extension, C, to reduce power consumption, code size, and memory use.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] There are also future plans to support hypervisors and virtualization.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] To name the combinations of functions that may be implemented, a nomenclature is defined to specify them in Chapter 27 of the current ratified Unprivileged ISA Specification.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] The instruction set base is specified first, coding for RISC-V, the register bit-width, and the variant; e.g., RV64I or RV32E.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] Then follows letters specifying implemented extensions, in the order of the above table.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] Each letter may be followed by a major optionally followed by "p" and a minor option number.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] It defaults to 0 if a minor version number is absent, and 1.0 if all of a version number is absent.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] Thus RV64IMAFD may be written as RV64I1p0M1p0A1p0F1p0D1p0 or more simply as RV64I1M1A1F1D1.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] Underscores may be used between extensions for readability, for example RV32I2_M2_A2.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] The base, extended integer & floating-point calculations, with synchronization primitives for multi-core computing, are considered to be necessary for general-purpose computing, and thus we have the shorthand, "G".
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] A small 32-bit computer for an embedded system might be RV32EC.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] A large 64-bit computer might be RV64GC; i.e., RV64IMAFDCZicsr_Zifencei.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] With the growth in the number of extensions, the standard now provides for extensions to be named by a single "Z" followed by an alphabetical name and an optional version number.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] For example, Zifencei names the instruction-fetch extension.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] Zifencei2 and Zifencei2p0 name version 2.0 of the same.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] The first letter following the "Z" by convention indicates the most closely related alphabetical extension category, IMAFDQLCBJTPVN.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] Thus the Zam extension for misaligned atomics relates to the "A" standard extension.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] Unlike single character extensions, Z extensions must be separated by underscores, grouped by category and then alphabetically within each category.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] Extensions specific to supervisor privilege level are named in the same way using "S" for prefix.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] Extensions specific to hypervisor level are named using "H" for prefix.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] Machine level extensions are prefixed with the three letters "Zxm".
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] Supervisor, hypervisor and machine level instruction set extensions are named after less privileged extensions.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] RISC-V developers may create their own non-standard instruction set extensions.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] These follow the "Z" naming convention, but with "X" as the prefix.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] They should be specified after all standard extensions, and if multiple non-standard extensions are listed, they should be listed alphabetically.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p01] Profiles and platforms for standard ISA choice lists are under discussion.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] As a RISC architecture, the RISC-V ISA is a load–store architecture.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Its floating-point instructions use IEEE 754 floating-point.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Notable features of the RISC-V ISA include: instruction bit field locations chosen to simplify the use of multiplexers in a CPU, a design that is architecturally neutral, and a fixed location for the sign bit of immediate values to speed up sign extension.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The instruction set is designed for a wide range of uses.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The base instruction set has a fixed length of 32-bit naturally aligned instructions, and the ISA supports variable length extensions where each instruction can be any number of 16-bit parcels in length.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Extensions support small embedded systems, personal computers, supercomputers with vector processors, and warehouse-scale parallel computers.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The instruction set specification defines 32-bit and 64-bit address space variants.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The specification includes a description of a 128-bit flat address space variant, as an extrapolation of 32- and 64-bit variants, but the 128-bit ISA remains "not frozen" intentionally, because as of 2023, there is still little practical experience with such large memory systems.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Unlike other academic designs which are typically optimized only for simplicity of exposition, the designers intended that the RISC-V instruction set be usable for practical computers.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] As of June 2019, version 2.2 of the user-space ISA and version 1.11 of the privileged ISA are frozen, permitting software and hardware development to proceed.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The user-space ISA, now renamed the Unprivileged ISA, was updated, ratified and frozen as version 20191213.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] An external debug specification is available as a draft, version 0.13.2.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] RISC-V has 32 integer registers (or 16 in the embedded variant), and when the floating-point extension is implemented, an additional 32 floating-point registers.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Except for memory access instructions, instructions address only registers.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The first integer register is a zero register, and the remainder are general-purpose registers.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] A store to the zero register has no effect, and a read always provides 0.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Using the zero register as a placeholder makes for a simpler instruction set.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Control and status registers exist, but user-mode programs can access only those used for performance measurement and floating-point management.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] No instructions exist to save and restore multiple registers.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Those were thought to be needless, too complex, and perhaps too slow.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Like many RISC designs, RISC-V is a load–store architecture: instructions address only registers, with load and store instructions conveying data to and from memory.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Most load and store instructions include a 12-bit offset and two register identifiers.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The other register is the destination (for a load) or the source (for a store).
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The offset is added to a base register to get the address.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Forming the address as a base register plus offset allows single instructions to access data structures.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] For example, if the base register points to the top of a stack, single instructions can access a subroutine's local variables in the stack.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Likewise the load and store instructions can access a record-style structure or a memory-mapped I/O device.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Using the constant zero register as a base address allows single instructions to access memory near address zero.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Memory is addressed as 8-bit bytes, with instructions being in little-endian order, and with data being in the byte order defined by the execution environment interface in which code is running.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Words, up to the register size, can be accessed with the load and store instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] RISC-V was originally specified as little-endian to resemble other familiar, successful computers, for example, x86.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] This also reduces a CPU's complexity and costs slightly less because it reads all sizes of words in the same order.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] For example, the RISC-V instruction set decodes starting at the lowest-addressed byte of the instruction.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Big-endian and bi-endian variants were defined for support of legacy code bases that assume big-endianness.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] An execution environment interface may allow accessed memory addresses not to be aligned to their word width, but accesses to aligned addresses may be faster; for example, simple CPUs may implement unaligned accesses with slow software emulation driven from an alignment failure interrupt.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Like many RISC instruction sets (and some complex instruction set computer (CISC) instruction sets, such as x86 and IBM System/360 and its successors through z/Architecture), RISC-V lacks address-modes that write back to the registers.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] For example, it does not auto-increment.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] RISC-V manages memory systems that are shared between CPUs or threads by ensuring a thread of execution always sees its memory operations in the programmed order.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] But between threads and I/O devices, RISC-V is simplified: it doesn't guarantee the order of memory operations, except by specific instructions, such as `fence`.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] A `fence` instruction guarantees that the results of predecessor operations are visible to successor operations of other threads or I/O devices.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] `fence` can guarantee the order of combinations of both memory and memory-mapped I/O operations.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] E.g. it can separate memory read and write operations, without affecting I/O operations.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Or, if a system can operate I/O devices in parallel with memory, `fence` doesn't force them to wait for each other.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] One CPU with one thread may decode `fence` as `nop`.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Some RISC CPUs (such as MIPS, PowerPC, DLX, and Berkeley's RISC-I) place 16 bits of offset in the loads and stores.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] They set the upper 16 bits by a *load upper word* instruction.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] This permits upper-halfword values to be set easily, without shifting bits.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] However, most use of the upper half-word instruction makes 32-bit constants, like addresses.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] RISC-V uses a SPARC-like combination of 12-bit offsets and 20-bit *set upper* instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The smaller 12-bit offset helps compact, 32-bit load and store instructions select two of 32 registers yet still have enough bits to support RISC-V's variable-length instruction coding.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] RISC-V handles 32-bit constants and addresses with instructions that set the upper 20 bits of a 32-bit register.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Load upper immediate `lui` loads 20 bits into bits 31 through 12.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Then a second instruction such as `addi` can set the bottom 12 bits.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Small numbers or addresses can be formed by using the zero register instead of `lui`.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] This method is extended to permit position-independent code by adding an instruction, `auipc` that generates 20 upper address bits by adding an offset to the program counter and storing the result into a base register.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] This permits a program to generate 32-bit addresses that are relative to the program counter.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The base register can often be used as-is with the 12-bit offsets of the loads and stores.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] If needed, `addi` can set the lower 12 bits of a register.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] In 64-bit and 128-bit ISAs,`lui` and `auipc` sign-extend the result to get the larger address.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Some fast CPUs may interpret combinations of instructions as single *fused* instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] `lui` or `auipc` are good candidates to fuse with `jalr`, `addi`, loads or stores.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] RISC-V's subroutine call `jal` (jump and link) places its return address in a register.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] This is faster in many computer designs, because it saves a memory access compared to systems that push a return address directly on a stack in memory.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] `jal` has a 20-bit signed (two's complement) offset.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The offset is multiplied by 2, then added to the PC (program counter) to generate a relative address to a 32-bit instruction.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] If the resulting address is not 32-bit aligned (i.e. evenly divisible by 4), the CPU may force an exception.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] RISC-V CPUs jump to calculated addresses using a *jump and link-register*, `jalr` instruction.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] `jalr` is similar to `jal`, but gets its destination address by adding a 12-bit offset to a base register.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] `jalr`'s bit format is like the register-relative loads and stores.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Like them, `jalr` can be used with the instructions that set the upper 20 bits of a base register to make 32-bit branches, either to an absolute address (using `lui`) or a PC-relative one (using `auipc` for position-independent code).
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] RISC-V recycles `jal` and `jalr` to get unconditional 20-bit PC-relative jumps and unconditional register-based 12-bit jumps.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Jumps just make the linkage register 0 so that no return address is saved.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] RISC-V also recycles `jalr` to return from a subroutine: To do this, `jalr`'s base register is set to be the linkage register saved by `jal` or `jalr`.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] `jalr`'s offset is zero and the linkage register is zero, so that there is no offset, and no return address is saved.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Like many RISC designs, in a subroutine call, a RISC-V compiler must use individual instructions to save registers to the stack at the start, and then restore these from the stack on exit.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] RISC-V has no *save multiple* or *restore multiple* register instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] These were thought to make the CPU too complex, and possibly slow.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Designers planned to reduce code size with library routines to save and restore registers.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] RISC-V has no condition code register or carry bit.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The designers believed that condition codes make fast CPUs more complex by forcing interactions between instructions in different stages of execution.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] This choice makes multiple-precision arithmetic more complex.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Also, a few numerical tasks need more energy.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] As a result, predication (the conditional execution of instructions) is not supported.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The designers claim that very fast, out-of-order CPU designs do predication anyway, by doing the comparison branch and conditional code in parallel, then discarding the unused path's effects.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] They also claim that even in simpler CPUs, predication is less valuable than branch prediction, which can prevent most stalls associated with conditional branches.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Code without predication is larger, with more branches, but they also claim that a compressed instruction set (such as RISC-V's set *C*) solves that problem in most cases.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Instead, RISC-V has short branches that perform comparisons: equal, not-equal, less-than, unsigned less-than, greater-than or equal and unsigned greater-than or equal.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Ten comparison-branch operations are implemented with only six instructions, by reversing the order of operands in the assembler.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] For example, *branch if greater than* can be done by *less-than* with a reversed order of operands.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The comparing branches have a twelve-bit signed range, and jump relative to the PC.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Unlike some RISC architectures, RISC-V does not include a branch delay slot, a position after a branch instruction that can be filled with an instruction that is executed whether or not the branch is taken.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] RISC-V omits a branch delay slot because it complicates multicycle CPUs, superscalar CPUs, and long pipelines.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Dynamic branch predictors have succeeded well enough to reduce the need for delayed branches.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] On the first encounter with a branch, RISC-V CPUs should assume that a negative relative branch (i.e. the sign bit of the offset is "1") will be taken.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] This assumes that a backward branch is a loop, and provides a default direction so that simple pipelined CPUs can fill their pipeline of instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Other than this, RISC-V does not require branch prediction, but core implementations are allowed to add it.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] RV32I reserves a "HINT" instruction space that presently does not contain any hints on branches; RV64I does the same.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] RISC-V segregates math into a minimal set of integer instructions (set *I*) with add, subtract, shift, bitwise logic and comparing-branches.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] These can simulate most of the other RISC-V instruction sets with software.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The integer multiplication instructions (set *M*) include signed and unsigned multiply and divide.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Double-precision integer multiplies and divides are included, as multiplies and divides that produce the *high word* of the result.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The ISA document recommends that implementors of CPUs and compilers *fuse* a standardized sequence of high and low multiply and divide instructions to one operation if possible.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The floating-point instructions (set *F*) include single-precision arithmetic and also comparison-branches similar to the integer arithmetic.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] It requires an additional set of 32 floating-point registers.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] These are separate from the integer registers.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The double-precision floating point instructions (set *D*) generally assume that the floating-point registers are 64-bit (i.e., double-width), and the *F* subset is coordinated with the *D* set.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] A quad-precision 128-bit floating-point ISA (*Q*) is also defined.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] RISC-V computers without floating-point can use a floating-point software library.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] RISC-V does not cause exceptions on arithmetic errors, including overflow, underflow, subnormal, and divide by zero.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Instead, both integer and floating-point arithmetic produce reasonable default values, and floating-point instructions set status bits.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Divide-by-zero can be discovered by one branch after the division.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The status bits can be tested by an operating system or periodic interrupt.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] RISC-V supports computers that share memory between multiple CPUs and threads.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] RISC-V's standard memory consistency model is release consistency.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] That is, loads and stores may generally be reordered, but some loads may be designated as *acquire* operations which must precede later memory accesses, and some stores may be designated as *release* operations which must follow earlier memory accesses.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The base instruction set includes minimal support in the form of a `fence` instruction to enforce memory ordering.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Although this is sufficient (`fence r, rw` provides *acquire* and `fence rw, w` provides *release*), combined operations can be more efficient.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The atomic memory operation extension supports two types of atomic memory operations for release consistency.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] First, it provides general purpose *load-reserved* `lr` and *store-conditional* `sc` instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] `lr` performs a load, and tries to reserve that address for its thread.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] A later store-conditional `sc` to the reserved address will be performed only if the reservation is not broken by an intervening store from another source.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] If the store succeeds, a zero is placed in a register.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] If it failed, a non-zero value indicates that software needs to retry the operation.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] In either case, the reservation is released.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The second group of atomic instructions perform read-modify-write sequences: a load (which is optionally a load-acquire) to a destination register, then an operation between the loaded value and a source register, then a store of the result (which may optionally be a store-release).
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Making the memory barriers optional permits combining the operations.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The optional operations are enabled by *acquire* and *release* bits which are present in every atomic instruction.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] RISC-V defines nine possible operations: swap (use source register value directly); add; bitwise and, or, and exclusive-or; and signed and unsigned minimum and maximum.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] A system design may optimize these combined operations more than `lr` and `sc`.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] For example, if the destination register for a swap is the constant zero, the load may be skipped.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] If the value stored is unmodified since the load, the store may be skipped.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] However, a simple load-type instruction is usually performed before the `cas` to fetch the old value.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The classic problem is that if a thread reads (loads) a value *A*, calculates a new value *C*, and then uses (`cas`) to replace *A* with *C*, it has no way to know whether concurrent activity in another thread has replaced *A* with some other value *B* and then restored the *A* in between.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] In some algorithms (e.g., ones in which the values in memory are pointers to dynamically allocated blocks), this ABA problem can lead to incorrect results.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The most common solution employs a *double-wide `cas`* instruction to update both the pointer and an adjacent counter; unfortunately, such an instruction requires a special instruction format to specify multiple registers, performs several reads and writes, and can have complex bus operation.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The `lr`/`sc` alternative is more efficient.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] It usually requires only one memory load, and minimizing slow memory operations is desirable.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] It's also exact: it controls all accesses to the memory cell, rather than just assuring a bit pattern.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] However, unlike `cas`, it can permit livelock, in which two or more threads repeatedly cause each other's instructions to fail.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] RISC-V guarantees forward progress (no livelock) if the code follows rules on the timing and sequence of instructions: 1) It must use only the *I* subset.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] 2) To prevent repetitive cache misses, the code (including the retry loop) must occupy no more than 16 consecutive instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] 3) It must include no system or fence instructions, or taken backward branches between the `lr` and `sc`.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] 4) The backward branch to the retry loop must be to the original sequence.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The specification gives an example of how to use the read-modify-write atomic instructions to lock a data structure.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The standard RISC-V ISA specifies that all instructions are 32 bits.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] This makes for a particularly simple implementation, but like other RISC processors with 32-bit instruction encoding, results in larger code size than in instruction sets with variable-length instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] To compensate, RISC-V's *32-bit* instructions are actually 30 bits; 3⁄4 of the opcode space is reserved for an optional (but recommended) variable-length *compressed* instruction set, RVC, that includes 16-bit instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] As in SuperH, ARM Thumb, and MIPS16, the compressed instructions are simply alternative encodings for a subset of the larger instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Like SuperH, but unlike the ARM or MIPS compressed sets, space was reserved from the start so there is no separate operating mode.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Standard and compressed instructions may be intermixed freely.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Because (like Thumb-1 and MIPS16) the compressed instructions are simply alternate encodings (aliases) for a selected subset of larger instructions, the compression can be implemented in the assembler, and it is not essential for the compiler to even know about it.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The prototype code was 20% smaller than an x86 PC and MIPS compressed code, and 2% larger than ARM Thumb-2 code.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] It also substantially reduced both the needed cache memory and the estimated power use of the memory system.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The researcher intended to reduce the code's binary size for small computers, especially embedded computer systems.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The prototype included 33 of the most frequently used instructions, recoded as compact 16-bit formats using operation codes previously reserved for the compressed set.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The compression was done in the assembler, with no changes to the compiler.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Compressed instructions omitted fields that are often zero, used small immediate values or accessed subsets (16 or 8) of the registers.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] `addi` is very common and often compressible.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Much of the difference in size compared to ARM's Thumb set occurred because RISC-V, and the prototype, have no instructions to save and restore multiple registers.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Instead, the compiler generated conventional instructions that access the stack.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The prototype RVC assembler then often converted these to compressed forms that were half the size.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] However, this still took more code space than the ARM instructions that save and restore multiple registers.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The researcher proposed to modify the compiler to call library routines to save and restore registers.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] These routines would tend to remain in a code cache and thus run fast, though probably not as fast as a save-multiple instruction.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Standard RVC requires occasional use of 32-bit instructions.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Several nonstandard RVC proposals are complete, requiring no 32-bit instructions, and are said to have higher densities than standard RVC.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Another proposal builds on these, and claims to use less coding range as well.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] An instruction set for the smallest *embedded* CPUs (set E) is reduced in other ways: Only 16 of the 32 integer registers are supported.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] All current extensions may be used; a floating-point extension to use the integer registers for floating-point values is being considered.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The privileged instruction set supports only machine mode, user mode and memory schemes that use base-and-bound address relocation.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Discussion has occurred for a microcontroller profile for RISC-V, to ease development of deeply embedded systems.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] It centers on faster, simple C-language support for interrupts, simplified security modes and a simplified POSIX application binary interface.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Correspondents have also proposed smaller, non-standard, 16-bit *RV16E* ISAs: Several serious proposals would use the 16-bit *C* instructions with 8 × 16-bit registers.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] An April fools' joke proposed a very practical arrangement: Utilize 16 × 16-bit integer registers, with the standard *EIMC* ISAs (including 32-bit instructions.) The joke was to use bank switching when a 32-bit CPU would be clearly superior with the larger address space.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] RISC-V's ISA includes a separate privileged instruction set specification, which mostly describes three privilege levels plus an orthogonal hypervisor mode.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] As of December 2021, version 1.12 is ratified by RISC-V International.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Systems with machine-mode, supervisor mode (for operating system) and user-modes for typical operating systems.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] These correspond roughly to systems with up to four ‘’rings’’ of privilege and security, at most: machine, hypervisor, supervisor and user.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Each layer also is expected to have a thin layer of standardized supporting software that communicates to a more-privileged layer, or hardware.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The ISA also includes a hypervisor mode that is orthogonal to the user and supervisor modes.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The basic feature is a configuration bit that either permits supervisor-level code to access hypervisor registers, or causes an interrupt on accesses.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] This bit lets supervisor mode directly handle the hardware needed by a hypervisor.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] This simplifies the implementation of hypervisors that are hosted by an operating system.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] This is a popular mode to run warehouse-scale computers.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] To support non-hosted hypervisors, the bit can cause these accesses to interrupt to a hypervisor.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The design also simplifies nesting of hypervisors, in which a hypervisor runs under a hypervisor, and if necessary it lets the kernel use hypervisor features within its own kernel code.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] As a result, the hypervisor form of the ISA supports five modes: machine, supervisor, user, supervisor-under-hypervisor and user-under-supervisor.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The privileged instruction set specification explicitly defines *hardware threads*, or *harts*.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Multiple hardware threads are a common practice in more-capable computers.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] When one thread is stalled, waiting for memory, others can often proceed.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Hardware threads can help make better use of the large number of registers and execution units in fast out-of-order CPUs.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Finally, hardware threads can be a simple, powerful way to handle interrupts: No saving or restoring of registers is required, simply executing a different hardware thread.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] However, the only hardware thread required in a RISC-V computer is thread zero.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Interrupts and exceptions are handled together.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Exceptions are caused by instruction execution including illegal instructions and system calls, while interrupts are caused by external events.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The existing control and status register definitions support RISC-V's error and memory exceptions, and a small number of interrupts, typically via an "advanced core local interruptor" (ACLINT).
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] For systems with more interrupts, the specification also defines a platform-level interrupt controller (PLIC) to coordinate large number of interrupts among multiple processors.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Interrupts always start at the highest-privileged machine level, and the control registers of each level have explicit *forwarding* bits to route interrupts to less-privileged code.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] For example, the hypervisor need not include software that executes on each interrupt to forward an interrupt to an operating system.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Instead, on set-up, it can set bits to forward the interrupt.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Several memory systems are supported in the specification.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Physical-only is suited to the simplest embedded systems.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] There are also four UNIX-style virtual memory systems for memory cached in mass-storage systems.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The virtual memory systems support MMU with four sizes, with addresses sized 32, 39, 48 and 57 bits.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] All virtual memory systems support 4 KiB pages, multilevel page-table trees and use very similar algorithms to walk the page table trees.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] All are designed for either hardware or software page-table walking.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] To optionally reduce the cost of page table walks, super-sized pages may be leaf pages in higher levels of a system's page table tree.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] SV32 is only supported on 32-bit implementations, has a two-layer page table tree and supports 4 MiB superpages.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] SV39 has a three level page table, and supports 2 MiB superpages and 1 GiB gigapages.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] It also has a 4-level page table and supports 2 MiB superpages, 1 GiB gigapages, and 512 GiB terapages.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] SV57 has a 5-level page table and supports 2 MiB superpages, 1 GiB gigapages, 512 GiB terapages and 256 TiB petapages.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Superpages are aligned on the page boundaries for the next-lowest size of page.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Some bit-manipulation ISA extensions were ratified in November 2021 (Zba, Zbb, Zbc, Zbs).
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The Zbs extension allows setting, getting, clearing, and toggling individual bits in a register by their index (bseti, bset, bexti, bext, bclri, bclr, binvi,binv).
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The Zbc extension has instructions for "carryless multiplication", which does the multiplication of polynomials over the Galois field GF(2) (clmul, clmulh, clmulr).
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] These are useful for cryptography and CRC checks of data integrity.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Done well, a more specialised bit-manipulation subset can aid cryptographic, graphic, and mathematical operations.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The criteria for inclusion documented in the draft were compliant with RISC-V philosophies and ISA formats, substantial improvements in code density or speed (i.e., at least a 3-for-1 reduction in instructions), and substantial real-world applications, including preexisting compiler support.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Version 0.93 of the bit-manipulation extension includes those instructions; some of them are now in version 1.0.1 of the scalar and entropy source instructions cryptography extension.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Packed-SIMD instructions are widely used by commercial CPUs to inexpensively accelerate multimedia and other digital signal processing.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] For simple, cost-reduced RISC-V systems, the base ISA's specification proposed to use the floating-point registers' bits to perform parallel single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) sub-word arithmetic.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] In 2017 a vendor published a more detailed proposal to the mailing list, and this can be cited as version 0.1.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] As of 2019, the efficiency of this proposed ISA varies from 2x to 5x a base CPU for a variety of DSP codecs.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The proposal lacked instruction formats and a license assignment to RISC-V International, but it was reviewed by the mailing list.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Some unpopular parts of this proposal were that it added a condition code, the first in a RISC-V design, linked adjacent registers (also a first), and has a loop counter that can be difficult to implement in some microarchitectures.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The proposed vector-processing instruction set may make the packed SIMD set obsolete.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] The designers hope to have enough flexibility that a CPU can implement vector instructions in a standard processor's registers.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] This would enable minimal implementations with similar performance to a multimedia ISA, as above.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] However, a true vector coprocessor could execute the same code with higher performance.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] As of 19 September 2021, the vector extension is at version 1.0.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] It is a conservative, flexible design of a general-purpose mixed-precision vector processor, suitable to execute compute kernels.
[src:arm-riscv/risc-v-p02] Code would port easily to CPUs with differing vector lengths, ideally without recompiling.
